WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.904 align:middle line:90%


00:00:05.904 --> 00:00:09.840 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:27.220 align:middle line:90%


00:00:27.220 --> 00:00:28.970 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA MEREDITH: I
don't know about you,

00:00:28.970 --> 00:00:30.990 align:middle line:10%
but I live my life to music.

00:00:30.990 --> 00:00:33.160 align:middle line:10%
When I wake up, I want to
hear one type of music.

00:00:33.160 --> 00:00:36.320 align:middle line:10%
As the day starts ramping up
in activity, I want another.

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:38.940 align:middle line:84%
And in those times of
great changes in life,

00:00:38.940 --> 00:00:41.720 align:middle line:84%
I need an epic piece
to signal a new era.

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:43.220 align:middle line:90%
Why is this so important?

00:00:43.220 --> 00:00:45.390 align:middle line:10%
Well, let's talk to Barry
Goldstein, the author

00:00:45.390 --> 00:00:47.040 align:middle line:10%
of "Secret Language
of the Heart,"

00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:49.560 align:middle line:10%
which is music, the secret
language of the heart.

00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:50.810 align:middle line:90%
>>BARRY GOLDSTEIN: Absolutely.

00:00:50.810 --> 00:00:54.100 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And you know,
I find it such a-- that's

00:00:54.100 --> 00:00:55.080 align:middle line:90%
how my day begins.

00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:56.930 align:middle line:84%
I make a cup of
tea, and then start

00:00:56.930 --> 00:01:00.010 align:middle line:84%
searching for the perfect
music for that day.

00:01:00.010 --> 00:01:02.170 align:middle line:84%
And so I can go through
and think, oh, maybe

00:01:02.170 --> 00:01:03.380 align:middle line:90%
a little Vivaldi, but no.

00:01:03.380 --> 00:01:04.180 align:middle line:90%
Mm-mm.

00:01:04.180 --> 00:01:05.459 align:middle line:90%
That's not working for me.

00:01:05.459 --> 00:01:07.560 align:middle line:84%
Go to something soft and
a little more emotional.

00:01:07.560 --> 00:01:08.530 align:middle line:90%
That's not it either.

00:01:08.530 --> 00:01:10.520 align:middle line:84%
And I'll go through
a lot of choices

00:01:10.520 --> 00:01:13.270 align:middle line:84%
until I find the thing that's
right for-- a right match

00:01:13.270 --> 00:01:15.950 align:middle line:84%
emotionally and
mentally for that moment

00:01:15.950 --> 00:01:17.230 align:middle line:90%
and what I need to do.

00:01:17.230 --> 00:01:17.700 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: That's amazing.

00:01:17.700 --> 00:01:17.860 align:middle line:90%
Perfect.

00:01:17.860 --> 00:01:18.940 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Is that what you do?

00:01:18.940 --> 00:01:19.570 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: It is.

00:01:19.570 --> 00:01:20.370 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:01:20.370 --> 00:01:23.610 align:middle line:10%
I think that's a starting
point with the secret language

00:01:23.610 --> 00:01:26.210 align:middle line:10%
of the heart is
really asking yourself

00:01:26.210 --> 00:01:29.490 align:middle line:10%
where you are in that moment,
where do you want to go,

00:01:29.490 --> 00:01:31.730 align:middle line:10%
and what piece of music is
going to take you there,

00:01:31.730 --> 00:01:33.140 align:middle line:10%
because music's a bridge.

00:01:33.140 --> 00:01:33.940 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It is.

00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:36.130 align:middle line:84%
It's like your
magic carpet ride.

00:01:36.130 --> 00:01:38.580 align:middle line:84%
And I have such deep
appreciation for it.

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:40.860 align:middle line:84%
And first of all,
so do other people.

00:01:40.860 --> 00:01:43.950 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I was just looking at
the endorsements on your book.

00:01:43.950 --> 00:01:45.560 align:middle line:84%
I thought, OK,
well, I think I've

00:01:45.560 --> 00:01:50.010 align:middle line:84%
interviewed all those-- Gregg
Braden, Don Miguel Ruiz--

00:01:50.010 --> 00:01:51.900 align:middle line:84%
many, many, many other
people that I would

00:01:51.900 --> 00:01:53.850 align:middle line:90%
have interviewed in this arena.

00:01:53.850 --> 00:01:55.990 align:middle line:84%
And then, of course,
Joe Dispenza.

00:01:55.990 --> 00:01:58.670 align:middle line:84%
What is it about
what you're doing

00:01:58.670 --> 00:02:03.830 align:middle line:84%
that has such wide support from
the community of people who

00:02:03.830 --> 00:02:07.190 align:middle line:84%
are considered, you know,
conscious media of one

00:02:07.190 --> 00:02:08.680 align:middle line:90%
kind or another?

00:02:08.680 --> 00:02:13.250 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Well, I think it
has to do with my intention

00:02:13.250 --> 00:02:15.480 align:middle line:90%
and what I put into the music.

00:02:15.480 --> 00:02:20.700 align:middle line:84%
And really, for me, it's
a complex system, music.

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:22.920 align:middle line:84%
It's not as simple
as it always sounds.

00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:23.720 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:30.180 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: So putting emotion
and intention and composition

00:02:30.180 --> 00:02:35.290 align:middle line:84%
and harmonics and creating a
recipe that is unique to each

00:02:35.290 --> 00:02:36.360 align:middle line:90%
one of those authors--

00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:37.160 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:39.950 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: --to support
their vision and what they

00:02:39.950 --> 00:02:41.460 align:middle line:90%
want to share with the world.

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:44.750 align:middle line:84%
So ultimately, I think
what the attraction

00:02:44.750 --> 00:02:47.770 align:middle line:84%
has been that I have an
understanding of what it takes

00:02:47.770 --> 00:02:51.020 align:middle line:84%
to bring people into their
hearts, because I've gone

00:02:51.020 --> 00:02:53.090 align:middle line:90%
and taken that journey myself.

00:02:53.090 --> 00:02:56.200 align:middle line:84%
And also to encourage
people to live

00:02:56.200 --> 00:02:59.630 align:middle line:84%
their heart and their passion
and how music can be a vehicle

00:02:59.630 --> 00:03:00.430 align:middle line:90%
to take them there.

00:03:00.430 --> 00:03:02.470 align:middle line:90%
It's a serious thing.

00:03:02.470 --> 00:03:03.800 align:middle line:90%
It's a fun thing.

00:03:03.800 --> 00:03:05.550 align:middle line:84%
But we all want
to have something

00:03:05.550 --> 00:03:07.260 align:middle line:90%
that supports our vision.

00:03:07.260 --> 00:03:10.220 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And it all comes down
to, basically, energy medicine.

00:03:10.220 --> 00:03:11.020 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: It is.

00:03:11.020 --> 00:03:11.600 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right?

00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:12.599 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Absolutely.

00:03:12.599 --> 00:03:15.310 align:middle line:90%
Music is a carrier of that.

00:03:15.310 --> 00:03:16.990 align:middle line:90%
Music creates its own field.

00:03:16.990 --> 00:03:17.930 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:03:17.930 --> 00:03:18.730 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:03:18.730 --> 00:03:19.050 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:19.050 --> 00:03:21.370 align:middle line:84%
So now one of the people
you work very closely with

00:03:21.370 --> 00:03:23.760 align:middle line:84%
is Dr. Joe Dispenza, whom
I've interviewed a few times.

00:03:23.760 --> 00:03:24.560 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: I do.

00:03:24.560 --> 00:03:25.643 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: We love Dr. Joe.

00:03:25.643 --> 00:03:28.090 align:middle line:90%
Everybody loves Dr. Joe.

00:03:28.090 --> 00:03:33.410 align:middle line:84%
And talk to us a little bit
about the more sciencey end

00:03:33.410 --> 00:03:35.290 align:middle line:90%
of what you do together.

00:03:35.290 --> 00:03:38.610 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Well, we
definitely are targeting

00:03:38.610 --> 00:03:41.160 align:middle line:90%
specific states of being.

00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:44.490 align:middle line:84%
So we know for a fact that
when the human body is

00:03:44.490 --> 00:03:48.480 align:middle line:84%
in a more coherent state, and
a lot of times that means more

00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:52.730 align:middle line:84%
smooth, orderly heart rhythms
that benefit our physical body,

00:03:52.730 --> 00:03:54.650 align:middle line:84%
then the body does
what it does best.

00:03:54.650 --> 00:03:58.940 align:middle line:84%
And that is heal or move to
that parasympathetic state.

00:03:58.940 --> 00:04:01.180 align:middle line:84%
So when we're working
together, this all kind of

00:04:01.180 --> 00:04:05.000 align:middle line:84%
goes into the recipe of bringing
people to those coherent heart

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:06.040 align:middle line:90%
states.

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:08.970 align:middle line:84%
And when we're doing that, we're
also working with brain states

00:04:08.970 --> 00:04:09.770 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:04:09.770 --> 00:04:14.760 align:middle line:84%
So we're targeting specific
brain states-- alpha, theta--

00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:17.829 align:middle line:84%
based on what is
going on in the group.

00:04:17.829 --> 00:04:21.220 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of times,
we're doing it live,

00:04:21.220 --> 00:04:23.190 align:middle line:84%
and we're doing
it in the moment.

00:04:23.190 --> 00:04:25.560 align:middle line:84%
So we're also
basing it on what's

00:04:25.560 --> 00:04:26.660 align:middle line:90%
going on in the audience.

00:04:26.660 --> 00:04:29.010 align:middle line:84%
We're feeling the
audience's energy.

00:04:29.010 --> 00:04:33.260 align:middle line:84%
And Dr. Joe was conducting
it and orchestrating it,

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:35.500 align:middle line:84%
and we had this back
and forth, where

00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:39.120 align:middle line:84%
the audience becomes an integral
part of the composition.

00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:40.910 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, you've
even gone as far

00:04:40.910 --> 00:04:43.910 align:middle line:84%
as working with
technology interfaces that

00:04:43.910 --> 00:04:47.490 align:middle line:84%
are reading the field or reading
your EEG, EKG, and so forth.

00:04:47.490 --> 00:04:51.240 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk a little bit about
that and what you and Dr. Joe

00:04:51.240 --> 00:04:52.470 align:middle line:90%
found.

00:04:52.470 --> 00:04:55.420 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Well, we found
that in these meditations,

00:04:55.420 --> 00:04:58.300 align:middle line:84%
people are moving to those
coherent brain wave states

00:04:58.300 --> 00:04:59.990 align:middle line:90%
in very short periods of time.

00:04:59.990 --> 00:05:02.615 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And you're witnessing
it via the technology involved.

00:05:02.615 --> 00:05:03.414 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Right.

00:05:03.414 --> 00:05:04.311 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:05:04.311 --> 00:05:05.310 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Neurofeedback.

00:05:05.310 --> 00:05:08.880 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Neurofeedback,
through heart methods also.

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:11.440 align:middle line:84%
Hooking people up through
the heart as well.

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:14.370 align:middle line:84%
And we're seeing that people
are moving to those alpha brain

00:05:14.370 --> 00:05:18.240 align:middle line:84%
wave states or theta states
in sometimes 10 seconds.

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:21.675 align:middle line:84%
They're showing that people
are moving into these states.

00:05:21.675 --> 00:05:26.960 align:middle line:84%
And it's a beautiful thing
to see scientifically.

00:05:26.960 --> 00:05:27.760 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:31.170 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: But you can see
it and feel it in the room

00:05:31.170 --> 00:05:31.970 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:05:31.970 --> 00:05:34.080 align:middle line:84%
You can see when
that audience or when

00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:36.520 align:middle line:84%
the people participating--
it's not an audience.

00:05:36.520 --> 00:05:41.170 align:middle line:84%
It's participants-- are moving
into a coherent state together.

00:05:41.170 --> 00:05:41.970 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:05:41.970 --> 00:05:45.780 align:middle line:84%
And one of the things I
noticed years ago in delving

00:05:45.780 --> 00:05:48.770 align:middle line:84%
into the whole neurofeedback
world and HeartMath

00:05:48.770 --> 00:05:54.230 align:middle line:84%
was that the heart was
noticed to slightly precede

00:05:54.230 --> 00:05:57.900 align:middle line:90%
the brain in response time.

00:05:57.900 --> 00:05:58.700 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Yes.

00:05:58.700 --> 00:06:02.274 align:middle line:84%
And that goes back and
forth between people.

00:06:02.274 --> 00:06:03.815 align:middle line:84%
We know that they
interact together--

00:06:03.815 --> 00:06:04.330 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: --Yes.

00:06:04.330 --> 00:06:04.960 align:middle line:90%
And people debate this.

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:06.030 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: That could
be an arm wrestling match.

00:06:06.030 --> 00:06:07.410 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: I remember
watching it.

00:06:07.410 --> 00:06:09.534 align:middle line:84%
I remember watching it with
both machines hooked up

00:06:09.534 --> 00:06:11.450 align:middle line:90%
simultaneously, even.

00:06:11.450 --> 00:06:14.490 align:middle line:84%
And I only bring it
up, because the wisdom

00:06:14.490 --> 00:06:18.400 align:middle line:84%
of the heart, our
knowledge from the heart,

00:06:18.400 --> 00:06:22.540 align:middle line:84%
it's not as though it's
some soft instrument that

00:06:22.540 --> 00:06:23.580 align:middle line:90%
lags behind.

00:06:23.580 --> 00:06:26.850 align:middle line:84%
It often is recognizing
truth and making a correction

00:06:26.850 --> 00:06:28.440 align:middle line:84%
before the brain
can even pick it up.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:29.240 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Right.

00:06:29.240 --> 00:06:29.810 align:middle line:90%
And they're working together.

00:06:29.810 --> 00:06:29.896 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:29.896 --> 00:06:30.800 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:06:30.800 --> 00:06:33.700 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: And that's where
we're becoming so much more

00:06:33.700 --> 00:06:36.520 align:middle line:84%
cognizant of heart
intelligence and how

00:06:36.520 --> 00:06:39.950 align:middle line:84%
to tap into that intelligence,
because they all follow.

00:06:39.950 --> 00:06:42.300 align:middle line:84%
When your heart is in
that relaxed state,

00:06:42.300 --> 00:06:46.020 align:middle line:84%
and you're in those smooth,
coherent, orderly rhythms,

00:06:46.020 --> 00:06:47.780 align:middle line:84%
are you going to be
in beta or high beta?

00:06:47.780 --> 00:06:48.580 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:06:48.580 --> 00:06:48.660 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:06:48.660 --> 00:06:51.030 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: The brain's
going to follow that,

00:06:51.030 --> 00:06:54.470 align:middle line:84%
and you're going to move into
that state, where your body can

00:06:54.470 --> 00:06:57.200 align:middle line:90%
move into rejuvenating itself.

00:06:57.200 --> 00:06:58.000 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.030 align:middle line:84%
And if you do want
to go to high beta,

00:07:00.030 --> 00:07:01.730 align:middle line:84%
well, there's plenty
of music for that.

00:07:01.730 --> 00:07:02.390 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: That's right.

00:07:02.390 --> 00:07:03.850 align:middle line:84%
And it's all about
targeting that.

00:07:03.850 --> 00:07:07.750 align:middle line:84%
It's not about a
one size fits all.

00:07:07.750 --> 00:07:10.780 align:middle line:84%
It's about where you're at
and where you want to go.

00:07:10.780 --> 00:07:17.380 align:middle line:84%
And there's science behind
preferred music now as well.

00:07:17.380 --> 00:07:21.100 align:middle line:84%
That preferred music that
you're choosing in the morning,

00:07:21.100 --> 00:07:22.860 align:middle line:84%
we're seeing more
and more that that's

00:07:22.860 --> 00:07:26.340 align:middle line:84%
proving to have very
beneficial effects not

00:07:26.340 --> 00:07:29.400 align:middle line:84%
only in day-to-day people's
lives in transformative ways,

00:07:29.400 --> 00:07:31.310 align:middle line:84%
but even in
Alzheimer's patients.

00:07:31.310 --> 00:07:32.380 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Mm-hm.

00:07:32.380 --> 00:07:33.180 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:07:33.180 --> 00:07:34.220 align:middle line:90%
Go ahead.

00:07:34.220 --> 00:07:38.270 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Well, we're finding
that music has such a strong

00:07:38.270 --> 00:07:44.720 align:middle line:84%
connection to memories that
your favorite song 40 years ago

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:49.890 align:middle line:84%
could now be your lifeline to
coming back into that memory

00:07:49.890 --> 00:07:51.830 align:middle line:90%
in a state of Alzheimer's.

00:07:51.830 --> 00:07:55.010 align:middle line:84%
So if I asked you as
an Alzheimer's person

00:07:55.010 --> 00:07:59.070 align:middle line:84%
who's going through that, do
you remember me and you and Mom

00:07:59.070 --> 00:08:01.550 align:middle line:90%
sitting together at Christmas?

00:08:01.550 --> 00:08:03.470 align:middle line:84%
And they might
not remember that.

00:08:03.470 --> 00:08:06.360 align:middle line:84%
But if you play
that Christmas song,

00:08:06.360 --> 00:08:08.870 align:middle line:84%
they might be able to
connect with that memory,

00:08:08.870 --> 00:08:12.710 align:middle line:84%
because the music opens up
another pathway to access that.

00:08:12.710 --> 00:08:13.600 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Absolutely.

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:15.530 align:middle line:84%
In fact, we're doing
that as a family

00:08:15.530 --> 00:08:20.390 align:middle line:84%
with my stepmother, who
is fairly far into decline

00:08:20.390 --> 00:08:25.150 align:middle line:84%
in dementia now, and starting
to play music from her era,

00:08:25.150 --> 00:08:27.520 align:middle line:90%
from the '40s, from the '50s.

00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:32.299 align:middle line:84%
And she'll go from a little
bit of-- when we do this,

00:08:32.299 --> 00:08:35.770 align:middle line:84%
I notice she'll go from this
bit of a foggy place, and boom.

00:08:35.770 --> 00:08:37.730 align:middle line:84%
She'll be wiggling
her little rear end

00:08:37.730 --> 00:08:39.460 align:middle line:90%
and dancing to the music.

00:08:39.460 --> 00:08:41.039 align:middle line:90%
It's so cute.

00:08:41.039 --> 00:08:42.289 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: That's a miracle.

00:08:42.289 --> 00:08:42.720 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That is.

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:45.020 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: It's a miracle
when we think about it,

00:08:45.020 --> 00:08:47.160 align:middle line:84%
and it's awesome that
we have these moments.

00:08:47.160 --> 00:08:50.080 align:middle line:84%
But in the life of the
families and the life

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:52.970 align:middle line:84%
of the patient, those small
moments where they can move out

00:08:52.970 --> 00:08:55.920 align:middle line:84%
of fear and anxiety and just
reconnect with that person

00:08:55.920 --> 00:08:57.680 align:middle line:90%
again, it's amazing.

00:08:57.680 --> 00:08:58.480 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:08:58.480 --> 00:08:59.896 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: And
Oliver Sacks, who

00:08:59.896 --> 00:09:03.720 align:middle line:84%
studies music and the
quickening, as he called it,

00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:06.520 align:middle line:84%
and watching patients
come to life,

00:09:06.520 --> 00:09:07.604 align:middle line:90%
he called it an awakening.

00:09:07.604 --> 00:09:08.403 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:09:08.403 --> 00:09:09.490 align:middle line:90%
That's what it looks like.

00:09:09.490 --> 00:09:12.010 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: And
that's no small feat.

00:09:12.010 --> 00:09:14.100 align:middle line:84%
I present in
medical conferences,

00:09:14.100 --> 00:09:17.520 align:middle line:84%
and we show videos of
Alzheimer's patients, who

00:09:17.520 --> 00:09:20.970 align:middle line:84%
are literally in head-down
positions and non-responsive,

00:09:20.970 --> 00:09:24.600 align:middle line:84%
and the role that music
plays within that.

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:27.950 align:middle line:84%
And I always ask, if I
would have shown you this

00:09:27.950 --> 00:09:32.270 align:middle line:84%
before and after picture without
telling you it was music,

00:09:32.270 --> 00:09:36.700 align:middle line:84%
would you have guessed that
music was the prescription that

00:09:36.700 --> 00:09:40.460 align:middle line:84%
got that person back to that
state, where they were now

00:09:40.460 --> 00:09:41.810 align:middle line:90%
here with us?

00:09:41.810 --> 00:09:43.300 align:middle line:90%
And most of them say no.

00:09:43.300 --> 00:09:44.100 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No.

00:09:44.100 --> 00:09:45.475 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Most
of them say no.

00:09:45.475 --> 00:09:50.490 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And yet it is such
a primitive, deep signaling

00:09:50.490 --> 00:09:52.642 align:middle line:90%
within our being-- music.

00:09:52.642 --> 00:09:54.600 align:middle line:84%
We'll talk a little later
about drumming, even,

00:09:54.600 --> 00:09:59.180 align:middle line:84%
but music where you add
melody to it, specifically.

00:09:59.180 --> 00:10:02.810 align:middle line:84%
And that's why as I said
when I was introducing you,

00:10:02.810 --> 00:10:06.000 align:middle line:84%
I find that if there's a
significant change in life

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:09.550 align:middle line:84%
going on, I have to find--
I'm kind of restless

00:10:09.550 --> 00:10:13.360 align:middle line:84%
until I find the album that
feels right in that changing

00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:14.310 align:middle line:90%
moment.

00:10:14.310 --> 00:10:17.210 align:middle line:84%
And then it signifies
that forever, really.

00:10:17.210 --> 00:10:19.580 align:middle line:84%
Forever, that time is
always brought back.

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:21.550 align:middle line:84%
But it's as though
we're reaching in

00:10:21.550 --> 00:10:24.140 align:middle line:84%
and need a different set of
frequencies when we change

00:10:24.140 --> 00:10:25.745 align:middle line:90%
anything within our own beings.

00:10:25.745 --> 00:10:28.100 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Yeah, and
you're creating new memories.

00:10:28.100 --> 00:10:31.560 align:middle line:84%
So while music has the ability
to connect us to old memories,

00:10:31.560 --> 00:10:35.160 align:middle line:84%
it also has the ability to shift
us out of old belief systems

00:10:35.160 --> 00:10:37.780 align:middle line:84%
and create completely
different new memories that

00:10:37.780 --> 00:10:38.580 align:middle line:90%
can lead us to--

00:10:38.580 --> 00:10:39.690 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Very good point.

00:10:39.690 --> 00:10:41.398 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: --elevated
emotions as well.

00:10:41.398 --> 00:10:45.800 align:middle line:84%
So not only does it work with
deprogramming or reprogramming

00:10:45.800 --> 00:10:49.417 align:middle line:84%
our past sometimes, but it
also programs our future.

00:10:49.417 --> 00:10:51.000 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That's an
interesting point.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:54.250 align:middle line:84%
Is it used in any way that you
know of kind of therapeutically

00:10:54.250 --> 00:10:57.360 align:middle line:84%
like that to break old patterns
and establish new learning

00:10:57.360 --> 00:10:59.400 align:middle line:90%
patterns, for example?

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:02.211 align:middle line:84%
Is music used in
learning environments?

00:11:02.211 --> 00:11:03.210 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Absolutely.

00:11:03.210 --> 00:11:03.570 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:11:03.570 --> 00:11:04.860 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Tell us about that.

00:11:04.860 --> 00:11:05.660 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Sure.

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:10.427 align:middle line:84%
Within ADHD children
who are in classes

00:11:10.427 --> 00:11:12.010 align:middle line:84%
who have a hard time
focusing, they're

00:11:12.010 --> 00:11:14.370 align:middle line:84%
seeing that music
actually helps them

00:11:14.370 --> 00:11:16.290 align:middle line:84%
bring more attention
with certain subjects

00:11:16.290 --> 00:11:17.850 align:middle line:90%
like arithmetic.

00:11:17.850 --> 00:11:18.660 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:11:18.660 --> 00:11:20.460 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: With
autistic children,

00:11:20.460 --> 00:11:24.160 align:middle line:84%
amazing things with
music, which really boosts

00:11:24.160 --> 00:11:26.430 align:middle line:84%
the emotional
intelligence, because they

00:11:26.430 --> 00:11:31.280 align:middle line:84%
have a lot of challenges with
connecting certain emotions

00:11:31.280 --> 00:11:33.030 align:middle line:90%
with that feeling.

00:11:33.030 --> 00:11:35.040 align:middle line:84%
So we can talk
about that, and we

00:11:35.040 --> 00:11:38.025 align:middle line:84%
can describe feelings and
get absolutely nowhere

00:11:38.025 --> 00:11:40.100 align:middle line:90%
with traditional language.

00:11:40.100 --> 00:11:42.830 align:middle line:84%
But music as a language,
when I put on a song

00:11:42.830 --> 00:11:47.860 align:middle line:84%
like "Happy" by Pharrell
and say, this is happy,

00:11:47.860 --> 00:11:50.770 align:middle line:84%
or I play a symphony
by Beethoven

00:11:50.770 --> 00:11:54.480 align:middle line:84%
that's in a minor
key, and this is sad.

00:11:54.480 --> 00:11:56.590 align:middle line:84%
Now moving forward,
they have a connection,

00:11:56.590 --> 00:11:58.990 align:middle line:84%
an experiential
connection with that,

00:11:58.990 --> 00:12:01.600 align:middle line:84%
where their emotional
intelligence is deepened.

00:12:01.600 --> 00:12:02.410 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:12:02.410 --> 00:12:03.210 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:03.210 --> 00:12:06.190 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about ADHD
and math, for example.

00:12:06.190 --> 00:12:09.300 align:middle line:84%
What would some-- because I know
that our viewers are thinking,

00:12:09.300 --> 00:12:10.800 align:middle line:84%
I wonder what that
would sound like.

00:12:10.800 --> 00:12:13.440 align:middle line:84%
What kind of music, for
example-- couple examples

00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:16.890 align:middle line:84%
of what would be good for
learning in that environment,

00:12:16.890 --> 00:12:17.690 align:middle line:90%
learning math.

00:12:17.690 --> 00:12:18.490 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Yeah.

00:12:18.490 --> 00:12:20.580 align:middle line:84%
And again, this is where
preferred music comes in,

00:12:20.580 --> 00:12:23.120 align:middle line:84%
because the music that's
going to help them focus

00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:25.400 align:middle line:90%
is music that they like.

00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:28.070 align:middle line:84%
So it's not like well when
you recommend vegetables,

00:12:28.070 --> 00:12:29.990 align:middle line:84%
because you know they're
good for kids, right?

00:12:29.990 --> 00:12:31.448 align:middle line:84%
When you recommend
your music, it's

00:12:31.448 --> 00:12:32.910 align:middle line:90%
probably not going to work.

00:12:32.910 --> 00:12:33.060 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:12:33.060 --> 00:12:34.330 align:middle line:90%
It's not one size fits all.

00:12:34.330 --> 00:12:36.640 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: So
creating a foundation

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:39.640 align:middle line:84%
within that, because that's
really-- there's distractions.

00:12:39.640 --> 00:12:42.510 align:middle line:84%
So music that are going to
create more foundations,

00:12:42.510 --> 00:12:47.370 align:middle line:84%
so popular music, which has a
verse, a chorus, a bridge, they

00:12:47.370 --> 00:12:48.890 align:middle line:90%
know where that song is going--

00:12:48.890 --> 00:12:49.090 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Percussion.

00:12:49.090 --> 00:12:50.381 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Percussion, right.

00:12:50.381 --> 00:12:52.090 align:middle line:84%
Rhythm to kind of
hold it down-- usually

00:12:52.090 --> 00:12:54.470 align:middle line:90%
work better in those conditions.

00:12:54.470 --> 00:12:55.790 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Interesting.

00:12:55.790 --> 00:12:59.670 align:middle line:84%
And well, I think you
answered a little bit

00:12:59.670 --> 00:13:03.250 align:middle line:84%
ago talking about working in the
environment with autistic kids.

00:13:03.250 --> 00:13:07.920 align:middle line:84%
And one thing with you, you were
a kid when this all started,

00:13:07.920 --> 00:13:09.580 align:middle line:84%
and I love the
story in your book

00:13:09.580 --> 00:13:12.350 align:middle line:84%
about your tiny,
tiny little mother.

00:13:12.350 --> 00:13:15.830 align:middle line:84%
You had this just wonderful
little angel of a mother,

00:13:15.830 --> 00:13:18.330 align:middle line:90%
who was 4'7".

00:13:18.330 --> 00:13:21.002 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: That's when
she had her hair done.

00:13:21.002 --> 00:13:21.960 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Without hair?

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:23.922 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: She's 4'5"
without her hair done.

00:13:23.922 --> 00:13:24.280 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, my god.

00:13:24.280 --> 00:13:27.030 align:middle line:84%
Just this tiny little woman,
but what a passion for music.

00:13:27.030 --> 00:13:29.900 align:middle line:84%
So let's start hearing
about your own life story

00:13:29.900 --> 00:13:32.460 align:middle line:84%
now, an introduction
and your mom to music.

00:13:32.460 --> 00:13:33.260 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Sure.

00:13:33.260 --> 00:13:36.520 align:middle line:84%
One thing I just wanted to
go back for one thing also

00:13:36.520 --> 00:13:39.840 align:middle line:84%
with ADHD, there's
also-- shows that there's

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:42.360 align:middle line:90%
a lack of dopamine within ADHD.

00:13:42.360 --> 00:13:44.080 align:middle line:84%
So there are studies
with music that

00:13:44.080 --> 00:13:46.910 align:middle line:84%
show that it helps to increase
dopamine levels, which is

00:13:46.910 --> 00:13:48.790 align:middle line:90%
based on our pleasure centers.

00:13:48.790 --> 00:13:50.630 align:middle line:84%
So it's important,
again, to have

00:13:50.630 --> 00:13:52.670 align:middle line:84%
them utilize their music
that brings pleasure.

00:13:52.670 --> 00:13:52.960 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:13:52.960 --> 00:13:54.130 align:middle line:90%
That makes total sense.

00:13:54.130 --> 00:13:54.930 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Yeah.

00:13:54.930 --> 00:13:57.930 align:middle line:84%
So I wanted to show the music
also has a pharmacy that's

00:13:57.930 --> 00:13:59.030 align:middle line:90%
created from it.

00:13:59.030 --> 00:14:00.600 align:middle line:90%
It's not just all pleasure.

00:14:00.600 --> 00:14:05.450 align:middle line:84%
It's our physical bodies are
producing specific-- a pharmacy

00:14:05.450 --> 00:14:06.510 align:middle line:90%
that benefits us.

00:14:06.510 --> 00:14:09.050 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: We're going to listen
to some cuts of your music

00:14:09.050 --> 00:14:12.240 align:middle line:84%
in a little bit, and maybe
you can even, at the time,

00:14:12.240 --> 00:14:14.510 align:middle line:84%
give us an idea of where
dopamine is coming in

00:14:14.510 --> 00:14:16.615 align:middle line:84%
versus, say,
serotonin coming in.

00:14:16.615 --> 00:14:17.415 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:14:17.415 --> 00:14:17.690 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: OK.

00:14:17.690 --> 00:14:18.620 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:14:18.620 --> 00:14:21.099 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So let's get
to your personal life

00:14:21.099 --> 00:14:22.140 align:middle line:90%
story for a little while.

00:14:22.140 --> 00:14:22.560 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Absolutely.

00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:23.590 align:middle line:90%
Sorry for interrupting.

00:14:23.590 --> 00:14:23.840 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No.

00:14:23.840 --> 00:14:26.173 align:middle line:84%
Go ahead and tell us about
your mom and how you started.

00:14:26.173 --> 00:14:29.400 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: So my mom
at a very young age,

00:14:29.400 --> 00:14:30.800 align:middle line:90%
put me behind a piano.

00:14:30.800 --> 00:14:32.440 align:middle line:90%
And this is in my book as well.

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:35.070 align:middle line:84%
It was very touching
to me still,

00:14:35.070 --> 00:14:37.410 align:middle line:84%
because it was such
a strong memory that

00:14:37.410 --> 00:14:42.400 align:middle line:84%
was embedded in me of literally
my mom's finger on top of mine

00:14:42.400 --> 00:14:44.950 align:middle line:84%
playing the song, "Yellow
Bird" by Harry Belafonte,

00:14:44.950 --> 00:14:47.570 align:middle line:84%
and she was singing,
"Yellow bird."

00:14:47.570 --> 00:14:50.740 align:middle line:84%
And I just remember
being in awe of how

00:14:50.740 --> 00:14:54.220 align:middle line:84%
the notes she was singing
were connected to the music

00:14:54.220 --> 00:14:57.420 align:middle line:84%
and how the notes hung
in the air of the room

00:14:57.420 --> 00:14:59.510 align:middle line:90%
and filled the space.

00:14:59.510 --> 00:15:03.570 align:middle line:84%
And I think it was my first
really transformational moment

00:15:03.570 --> 00:15:07.350 align:middle line:84%
with music, where I just
knew on a heart level

00:15:07.350 --> 00:15:10.970 align:middle line:84%
that music was always
going to be in my life.

00:15:10.970 --> 00:15:15.160 align:middle line:84%
And so throughout my life,
I was nurtured very much

00:15:15.160 --> 00:15:22.730 align:middle line:84%
within my household, and through
the ranks, learned guitar.

00:15:22.730 --> 00:15:25.980 align:middle line:84%
And for me, it was
always a way to tap

00:15:25.980 --> 00:15:27.700 align:middle line:90%
into a state of creation.

00:15:27.700 --> 00:15:29.370 align:middle line:84%
That's always been
my primary thing.

00:15:29.370 --> 00:15:32.530 align:middle line:84%
It's like I remember sitting
on the edge of my bed

00:15:32.530 --> 00:15:36.480 align:middle line:84%
and learning three chords
and writing a song to that

00:15:36.480 --> 00:15:40.980 align:middle line:84%
and saying, oh, my god, this did
not exist a half an hour ago.

00:15:40.980 --> 00:15:46.130 align:middle line:84%
Being able to create with
music and always a vehicle

00:15:46.130 --> 00:15:50.500 align:middle line:84%
to share my passion,
to share my purpose.

00:15:50.500 --> 00:15:53.620 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's what
really motivates me with music

00:15:53.620 --> 00:15:56.820 align:middle line:84%
is utilizing it as a
tool to help people

00:15:56.820 --> 00:16:00.840 align:middle line:84%
reach their passion and their
purpose, to kind of move

00:16:00.840 --> 00:16:04.080 align:middle line:84%
to that vulnerable, naked
state, where we can reconnect

00:16:04.080 --> 00:16:06.080 align:middle line:90%
with our heart and find that.

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:09.260 align:middle line:84%
And so many times, when we're in
illness and health challenges,

00:16:09.260 --> 00:16:12.800 align:middle line:84%
we lose that conversation
with our hearts,

00:16:12.800 --> 00:16:15.740 align:middle line:84%
because we're in
a state of fear.

00:16:15.740 --> 00:16:18.560 align:middle line:84%
And we need to reconnect,
and music restarts

00:16:18.560 --> 00:16:20.430 align:middle line:90%
that beautiful conversation.

00:16:20.430 --> 00:16:22.805 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And as you're talking,
what I'm feeling in this

00:16:22.805 --> 00:16:27.310 align:middle line:84%
and what strikes me is that
it was also this family

00:16:27.310 --> 00:16:31.210 align:middle line:84%
bonding, this love-- music
and love and your mother's

00:16:31.210 --> 00:16:32.010 align:middle line:90%
generous spirit.

00:16:32.010 --> 00:16:34.410 align:middle line:84%
None of that can
be separated out

00:16:34.410 --> 00:16:36.320 align:middle line:84%
when you started with
your musical roots.

00:16:36.320 --> 00:16:37.120 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:16:37.120 --> 00:16:38.161 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: That's true.

00:16:38.161 --> 00:16:39.880 align:middle line:90%
I never thought of it that way.

00:16:39.880 --> 00:16:42.900 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And it
just shows how music

00:16:42.900 --> 00:16:46.230 align:middle line:84%
can be used within the
family dynamic also,

00:16:46.230 --> 00:16:48.980 align:middle line:84%
how healing it is
within a family dynamic

00:16:48.980 --> 00:16:52.680 align:middle line:84%
if even one person
takes up an instrument.

00:16:52.680 --> 00:16:54.280 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about
that a little bit,

00:16:54.280 --> 00:16:57.760 align:middle line:84%
about, say, one child
in a family of five

00:16:57.760 --> 00:16:59.310 align:middle line:90%
takes up the piano.

00:16:59.310 --> 00:17:00.110 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Right

00:17:00.110 --> 00:17:02.220 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And the
potential for what that

00:17:02.220 --> 00:17:03.220 align:middle line:90%
brings to that family.

00:17:03.220 --> 00:17:04.470 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Well, absolutely.

00:17:04.470 --> 00:17:05.270 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:17:05.270 --> 00:17:07.020 align:middle line:84%
And my sister was
a piano player,

00:17:07.020 --> 00:17:09.290 align:middle line:84%
and she was more
technically based,

00:17:09.290 --> 00:17:13.640 align:middle line:84%
and she went to high school in
music in art and took lessons,

00:17:13.640 --> 00:17:16.849 align:middle line:84%
and I was kind of the other
way, where I wasn't really

00:17:16.849 --> 00:17:20.060 align:middle line:84%
taught a lot of the
technical aspects of music.

00:17:20.060 --> 00:17:22.980 align:middle line:84%
And I was more
improvisational, so

00:17:22.980 --> 00:17:26.450 align:middle line:84%
a perfect aspect of how music
affects both the right and left

00:17:26.450 --> 00:17:27.250 align:middle line:90%
side of the brain.

00:17:27.250 --> 00:17:28.062 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:17:28.062 --> 00:17:30.020 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: And you
know, it obviously creates

00:17:30.020 --> 00:17:31.380 align:middle line:90%
bonding in the family as well.

00:17:31.380 --> 00:17:33.564 align:middle line:90%
We had our own concerts.

00:17:33.564 --> 00:17:35.230 align:middle line:84%
It was like the time
of Donny and Marie,

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:39.910 align:middle line:84%
so we were like the Donny and
Marie of the Bronx, you know.

00:17:39.910 --> 00:17:43.900 align:middle line:84%
And you know, it brought the
family closer together as well.

00:17:43.900 --> 00:17:45.070 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:17:45.070 --> 00:17:46.860 align:middle line:84%
And that was probably
my favorite part

00:17:46.860 --> 00:17:49.130 align:middle line:84%
of raising my son,
because he was naturally

00:17:49.130 --> 00:17:53.480 align:middle line:84%
good at music, not a
great student, dyslexic.

00:17:53.480 --> 00:17:55.490 align:middle line:90%
Really hard to read music.

00:17:55.490 --> 00:17:56.900 align:middle line:90%
Just kind of slogged through it.

00:17:56.900 --> 00:17:58.090 align:middle line:90%
But he could create.

00:17:58.090 --> 00:17:59.190 align:middle line:90%
He could compose.

00:17:59.190 --> 00:18:03.380 align:middle line:84%
And either way, I just--
some of the happiest days

00:18:03.380 --> 00:18:06.520 align:middle line:84%
were just being in the
background of his life,

00:18:06.520 --> 00:18:10.340 align:middle line:84%
while he was playing
the piano or the guitar

00:18:10.340 --> 00:18:11.262 align:middle line:90%
and falling asleep.

00:18:11.262 --> 00:18:12.970 align:middle line:84%
Often, he'd be practicing
later at night,

00:18:12.970 --> 00:18:14.670 align:middle line:90%
and falling asleep to that.

00:18:14.670 --> 00:18:17.940 align:middle line:84%
It just added so much
love to the household.

00:18:17.940 --> 00:18:18.840 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Right.

00:18:18.840 --> 00:18:22.280 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Which I-- when I was
a kid and playing the piano,

00:18:22.280 --> 00:18:23.660 align:middle line:90%
it wasn't like that.

00:18:23.660 --> 00:18:26.590 align:middle line:84%
It's like, would you please
stop playing the same song

00:18:26.590 --> 00:18:29.020 align:middle line:90%
over and over?

00:18:29.020 --> 00:18:30.560 align:middle line:90%
It was like, oh, OK.

00:18:30.560 --> 00:18:32.750 align:middle line:84%
So they put the piano
in my bedroom, locked me

00:18:32.750 --> 00:18:36.864 align:middle line:84%
in there, just-- I'd stay in
all weekend to learn a new song.

00:18:36.864 --> 00:18:38.780 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Well,
initially, I was a drummer,

00:18:38.780 --> 00:18:40.240 align:middle line:84%
and I lived in an
apartment complex.

00:18:40.240 --> 00:18:40.500 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, no.

00:18:40.500 --> 00:18:41.596 align:middle line:90%
That's especially irritating.

00:18:41.596 --> 00:18:43.137 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: So that
kind of went out

00:18:43.137 --> 00:18:44.925 align:middle line:90%
the window within that.

00:18:44.925 --> 00:18:47.337 align:middle line:84%
But 40 years ago,
if you would've

00:18:47.337 --> 00:18:48.920 align:middle line:84%
told me I would've
been putting people

00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:52.320 align:middle line:84%
to sleep every night with
music as a rock musician,

00:18:52.320 --> 00:18:54.130 align:middle line:84%
I would have considered
that insulting.

00:18:54.130 --> 00:18:59.310 align:middle line:84%
But now being part
of people's solutions

00:18:59.310 --> 00:19:03.137 align:middle line:84%
to be able to sleep at
night is such a big thing.

00:19:03.137 --> 00:19:04.345 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It's not an insult.

00:19:04.345 --> 00:19:05.636 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: It's a compliment.

00:19:05.636 --> 00:19:08.130 align:middle line:84%
It's not that I'm recognized
in the Metamucil aisle.

00:19:08.130 --> 00:19:09.620 align:middle line:90%
Oh, that's Barry Goldstein.

00:19:09.620 --> 00:19:11.644 align:middle line:90%
He puts me to sleep every night.

00:19:11.644 --> 00:19:12.550 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:19:12.550 --> 00:19:13.350 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:13.350 --> 00:19:16.100 align:middle line:84%
So your life, after-- you played
music throughout your life,

00:19:16.100 --> 00:19:18.250 align:middle line:84%
and you decided to go into
the recording industry.

00:19:18.250 --> 00:19:19.842 align:middle line:90%
And you were back east, right?

00:19:19.842 --> 00:19:21.300 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: I was
back east, yeah.

00:19:21.300 --> 00:19:23.340 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: No,
that's, as I recall,

00:19:23.340 --> 00:19:27.430 align:middle line:84%
you said it took something like
100, 150 hours to put together

00:19:27.430 --> 00:19:28.610 align:middle line:90%
a four-minute piece.

00:19:28.610 --> 00:19:28.950 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Right.

00:19:28.950 --> 00:19:31.408 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And there is a lot
of stress that goes with this.

00:19:31.408 --> 00:19:34.920 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about your life
and how that transition

00:19:34.920 --> 00:19:38.030 align:middle line:84%
and just grinding out
the technical aspects,

00:19:38.030 --> 00:19:38.864 align:middle line:90%
how it affected you.

00:19:38.864 --> 00:19:39.663 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Yeah.

00:19:39.663 --> 00:19:41.260 align:middle line:84%
I think a lot of
times when we're

00:19:41.260 --> 00:19:45.110 align:middle line:84%
moving to what we want
to be when we're a kid,

00:19:45.110 --> 00:19:48.220 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't always pan out the
way that you thought it did.

00:19:48.220 --> 00:19:50.400 align:middle line:84%
So I always wanted to be
a professional musician,

00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:53.705 align:middle line:84%
and wow, imagine just being
able to do that as a livelihood.

00:19:53.705 --> 00:19:55.080 align:middle line:84%
And then when I
got to that point

00:19:55.080 --> 00:19:58.610 align:middle line:84%
where I could, and I was
doing that, what I noticed

00:19:58.610 --> 00:20:01.100 align:middle line:90%
was that I was losing my heart.

00:20:01.100 --> 00:20:04.380 align:middle line:84%
I was losing contact with
that 14-year-old kid sitting

00:20:04.380 --> 00:20:08.780 align:middle line:84%
on the edge of his bed, who was
like enthralled to be writing

00:20:08.780 --> 00:20:09.840 align:middle line:90%
a song.

00:20:09.840 --> 00:20:14.910 align:middle line:84%
And so I really, in that process
of creating the 100-hour songs,

00:20:14.910 --> 00:20:19.750 align:middle line:84%
I was losing my love in the mix
of deadlines and commitments

00:20:19.750 --> 00:20:21.840 align:middle line:90%
like everybody else was.

00:20:21.840 --> 00:20:27.270 align:middle line:84%
And I started asking myself,
how do I get back to that place,

00:20:27.270 --> 00:20:30.900 align:middle line:84%
where I can connect,
again, music with my heart?

00:20:30.900 --> 00:20:33.910 align:middle line:84%
And it was an experiment,
really, for me.

00:20:33.910 --> 00:20:36.610 align:middle line:84%
And I started doing
some online research,

00:20:36.610 --> 00:20:41.700 align:middle line:84%
and I found out that the
human heart at a relaxed state

00:20:41.700 --> 00:20:45.030 align:middle line:84%
beats between 60 and
70 beats per minute

00:20:45.030 --> 00:20:46.314 align:middle line:90%
depending on the person.

00:20:46.314 --> 00:20:47.730 align:middle line:84%
I was like, wow,
what would happen

00:20:47.730 --> 00:20:50.560 align:middle line:84%
if I took the
pressure off myself,

00:20:50.560 --> 00:20:54.280 align:middle line:84%
and I just started taking
these hour-long journeys

00:20:54.280 --> 00:20:57.210 align:middle line:84%
with my metronome set
at 60 beats per minute?

00:20:57.210 --> 00:20:58.130 align:middle line:90%
And as my--

00:20:58.130 --> 00:20:58.850 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Just playing to it.

00:20:58.850 --> 00:21:00.433 align:middle line:84%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Yeah,
just playing to it,

00:21:00.433 --> 00:21:02.570 align:middle line:84%
and allowing myself
to resynchronize

00:21:02.570 --> 00:21:04.740 align:middle line:90%
in the process of composing.

00:21:04.740 --> 00:21:06.770 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And you became
your own physician.

00:21:06.770 --> 00:21:07.570 align:middle line:90%
>>GOLDSTEIN: Yeah.

00:21:07.570 --> 00:21:09.870 align:middle line:84%
I really did, because I
didn't think anyone would

00:21:09.870 --> 00:21:11.090 align:middle line:90%
be listening to this music.

00:21:11.090 --> 00:21:15.170 align:middle line:84%
But I realized in that state,
I was moving to the zone.

00:21:15.170 --> 00:21:17.550 align:middle line:84%
I was resynchronizing
with my heart.

00:21:17.550 --> 00:21:18.350 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:21:18.350 --> 00:21:19.391 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: How does that go?

00:21:19.391 --> 00:21:22.665 align:middle line:84%
Do 60 per second with just
that beats, so people feel it.

00:21:22.665 --> 00:21:28.458 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: It would
probably be-- boom.

00:21:28.458 --> 00:21:32.064 align:middle line:84%
[COUNTING BEATS]
Somewhere in there.

00:21:32.064 --> 00:21:33.730 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: So it's almost
a hypnotic state.

00:21:33.730 --> 00:21:35.180 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: It is.

00:21:35.180 --> 00:21:39.410 align:middle line:84%
You move into it very easily,
because that metronome that's

00:21:39.410 --> 00:21:43.010 align:middle line:84%
in the music-- and this is
the powerful part to me.

00:21:43.010 --> 00:21:45.280 align:middle line:84%
You have a metronome
in your heart.

00:21:45.280 --> 00:21:46.930 align:middle line:90%
Your heart is a metronome.

00:21:46.930 --> 00:21:52.210 align:middle line:84%
And it has the ability to
adapt to a musical piece.

00:21:52.210 --> 00:21:54.120 align:middle line:84%
So when we're listening
to that music,

00:21:54.120 --> 00:21:57.380 align:middle line:84%
it's just like effortlessly
coming into that space

00:21:57.380 --> 00:22:00.140 align:middle line:90%
of moving back into the heart.

00:22:00.140 --> 00:22:02.050 align:middle line:84%
And that's really
what it did for me.

00:22:02.050 --> 00:22:05.370 align:middle line:84%
It moved me back into my
heart, and I started composing.

00:22:05.370 --> 00:22:09.552 align:middle line:84%
I created six CDs worth of
material with that thinking

00:22:09.552 --> 00:22:10.510 align:middle line:90%
no one would ever hear.

00:22:10.510 --> 00:22:11.780 align:middle line:90%
These were for me.

00:22:11.780 --> 00:22:14.340 align:middle line:84%
And people ended up using
them to birth their children

00:22:14.340 --> 00:22:22.360 align:middle line:84%
into the world, for sleeping
challenges, for dementia.

00:22:22.360 --> 00:22:23.950 align:middle line:90%
My friend's mom had dementia.

00:22:23.950 --> 00:22:25.960 align:middle line:90%
Can I try one of your pieces?

00:22:25.960 --> 00:22:29.490 align:middle line:84%
And she ended up
using it every night.

00:22:29.490 --> 00:22:32.540 align:middle line:84%
She started calling
it her music.

00:22:32.540 --> 00:22:35.080 align:middle line:84%
And at the end of the
circle of life and hospice,

00:22:35.080 --> 00:22:38.760 align:middle line:84%
where people are needing
to move out of that

00:22:38.760 --> 00:22:43.030 align:middle line:84%
contracted state and move
into a more expensive state

00:22:43.030 --> 00:22:43.830 align:middle line:90%
to transition.

00:22:43.830 --> 00:22:44.630 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Make the transition.

00:22:44.630 --> 00:22:44.870 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:22:44.870 --> 00:22:46.080 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Exactly.

00:22:46.080 --> 00:22:49.800 align:middle line:84%
So what started as an
experiment for me ended up

00:22:49.800 --> 00:22:52.950 align:middle line:84%
being an amazing
process of assisting

00:22:52.950 --> 00:22:56.740 align:middle line:84%
myself and others to
use them beneficially

00:22:56.740 --> 00:22:59.370 align:middle line:90%
and in medical settings as well.

00:22:59.370 --> 00:23:04.410 align:middle line:84%
And that really sparked my
intention of writing the book

00:23:04.410 --> 00:23:09.590 align:middle line:84%
and finding out more about
why that was happening.

00:23:09.590 --> 00:23:15.740 align:middle line:84%
And research over an extended
period of time as well.

00:23:15.740 --> 00:23:17.780 align:middle line:84%
My fiancee was a
big part of that,

00:23:17.780 --> 00:23:22.340 align:middle line:84%
and she was using my music
in her clinics for insomnia.

00:23:22.340 --> 00:23:24.250 align:middle line:84%
And when I told
her my intention is

00:23:24.250 --> 00:23:27.110 align:middle line:84%
I want to get this
out there medically,

00:23:27.110 --> 00:23:29.490 align:middle line:84%
and it became all
about, OK, well,

00:23:29.490 --> 00:23:31.920 align:middle line:90%
we have to speak that language.

00:23:31.920 --> 00:23:35.210 align:middle line:84%
And the language that
creates that opening

00:23:35.210 --> 00:23:37.240 align:middle line:84%
is the language of
science and research.

00:23:37.240 --> 00:23:38.040 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Right.

00:23:38.040 --> 00:23:38.956 align:middle line:90%
And she's big on that.

00:23:38.956 --> 00:23:40.620 align:middle line:84%
We're talking about
Dr. Donese Worden.

00:23:40.620 --> 00:23:41.080 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Yes.

00:23:41.080 --> 00:23:41.530 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Yes.

00:23:41.530 --> 00:23:43.630 align:middle line:84%
And so the two of you
have been collaborating,

00:23:43.630 --> 00:23:47.340 align:middle line:84%
because her thing is energy
medicine in large part.

00:23:47.340 --> 00:23:49.720 align:middle line:84%
And so between the
two of you, you

00:23:49.720 --> 00:23:52.980 align:middle line:84%
had the ability to begin almost
running your own research.

00:23:52.980 --> 00:23:53.780 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Exactly.

00:23:53.780 --> 00:23:56.910 align:middle line:84%
And my music this year
is being researched

00:23:56.910 --> 00:24:00.150 align:middle line:84%
by several universities,
where in conjunction with Dr.

00:24:00.150 --> 00:24:03.290 align:middle line:84%
Daniel Amen, to
conduct more research.

00:24:03.290 --> 00:24:04.862 align:middle line:84%
We've been talking
about our health.

00:24:04.862 --> 00:24:07.070 align:middle line:84%
So I think we're at a good
time in our consciousness,

00:24:07.070 --> 00:24:11.180 align:middle line:84%
where people are starting to
understand that music moves

00:24:11.180 --> 00:24:12.730 align:middle line:90%
beyond art and entertainment.

00:24:12.730 --> 00:24:13.530 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Yes..

00:24:13.530 --> 00:24:15.300 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: And it's
a support mechanism

00:24:15.300 --> 00:24:21.130 align:middle line:84%
for a lot of health
challenges and chronic issues,

00:24:21.130 --> 00:24:24.540 align:middle line:84%
as well as being low
cost and noninvasive.

00:24:24.540 --> 00:24:25.540 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: And pleasurable.

00:24:25.540 --> 00:24:26.665 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: And pleasurable.

00:24:26.665 --> 00:24:27.670 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:24:27.670 --> 00:24:30.220 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: Bringing about all
the cascade of the good brain

00:24:30.220 --> 00:24:31.020 align:middle line:90%
chemicals.

00:24:31.020 --> 00:24:31.470 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: That's right.

00:24:31.470 --> 00:24:33.690 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: Let's talk about the
Sacred Heartbeat Process.

00:24:33.690 --> 00:24:34.490 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: OK.

00:24:34.490 --> 00:24:35.780 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:24:35.780 --> 00:24:41.000 align:middle line:84%
Well, I created this process
when I lived in New York,

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:43.670 align:middle line:84%
and so my recording
studio was 15 blocks away.

00:24:43.670 --> 00:24:46.330 align:middle line:84%
And I would start my day
as you do with music,

00:24:46.330 --> 00:24:47.890 align:middle line:90%
and I would be all zenned out.

00:24:47.890 --> 00:24:49.340 align:middle line:90%
Oh, it's going to be an amazing.

00:24:49.340 --> 00:24:54.570 align:middle line:84%
And in 15 blocks, I would move
through a multitude of sounds

00:24:54.570 --> 00:24:58.760 align:middle line:84%
and things going on, everything
from people begging for money

00:24:58.760 --> 00:24:59.655 align:middle line:90%
to smells--

00:24:59.655 --> 00:25:00.970 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Taxis honking.

00:25:00.970 --> 00:25:04.070 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: Taxis honking,
ambulances, and by the time

00:25:04.070 --> 00:25:05.690 align:middle line:84%
I got to my recording
studio, and I

00:25:05.690 --> 00:25:07.940 align:middle line:84%
wanted to be in that
state of creation,

00:25:07.940 --> 00:25:10.800 align:middle line:84%
I realized that I was
in a contracted state.

00:25:10.800 --> 00:25:12.780 align:middle line:84%
And I wasn't in that
expansive state,

00:25:12.780 --> 00:25:16.530 align:middle line:84%
where I could connect
and bring music through.

00:25:16.530 --> 00:25:18.650 align:middle line:84%
So I wanted to create
a process that I

00:25:18.650 --> 00:25:22.080 align:middle line:84%
could do in very short periods
of time that would put me back

00:25:22.080 --> 00:25:23.840 align:middle line:90%
in contact with my heart.

00:25:23.840 --> 00:25:25.740 align:middle line:90%
That's where I create from.

00:25:25.740 --> 00:25:30.360 align:middle line:84%
So what better way than
to touch our hearts?

00:25:30.360 --> 00:25:32.890 align:middle line:84%
And I just really feel
strongly about this

00:25:32.890 --> 00:25:35.750 align:middle line:90%
that we've lost connection.

00:25:35.750 --> 00:25:38.140 align:middle line:84%
Many of us say that we want
to lead a more heart-centered

00:25:38.140 --> 00:25:40.252 align:middle line:84%
life, but when you
ask someone, OK, well,

00:25:40.252 --> 00:25:41.710 align:middle line:84%
when was the last
time you actually

00:25:41.710 --> 00:25:45.380 align:middle line:84%
listened to your heart, we
have a whole inner symphony.

00:25:45.380 --> 00:25:47.720 align:middle line:90%
I call this our inner music.

00:25:47.720 --> 00:25:50.690 align:middle line:84%
So the Sacred
Heartbeat Process is

00:25:50.690 --> 00:25:53.560 align:middle line:84%
geared towards putting
your hands on your heart,

00:25:53.560 --> 00:25:56.790 align:middle line:84%
and you start by
taking a big breath in.

00:25:56.790 --> 00:26:00.270 align:middle line:84%
You bring that breath in all
the way through your feet,

00:26:00.270 --> 00:26:03.180 align:middle line:84%
moving through your lower body,
all the way up to the heart.

00:26:03.180 --> 00:26:04.590 align:middle line:90%
And then you release it.

00:26:04.590 --> 00:26:07.940 align:middle line:90%
So if it'd be kind of like this.

00:26:07.940 --> 00:26:10.720 align:middle line:90%
And out.

00:26:10.720 --> 00:26:12.720 align:middle line:84%
And then the second breath,
you move that breath

00:26:12.720 --> 00:26:14.480 align:middle line:90%
in through the top of your head.

00:26:14.480 --> 00:26:16.170 align:middle line:84%
You move it through
your upper body,

00:26:16.170 --> 00:26:17.700 align:middle line:90%
through your upper centers.

00:26:17.700 --> 00:26:19.980 align:middle line:90%
You breathe into the heart.

00:26:19.980 --> 00:26:22.270 align:middle line:90%
And you release it.

00:26:22.270 --> 00:26:25.800 align:middle line:84%
And then you take a breath
in through the heart,

00:26:25.800 --> 00:26:29.260 align:middle line:84%
and a breath out
through the heart.

00:26:29.260 --> 00:26:32.290 align:middle line:84%
And what happens is you
start to really reconnect

00:26:32.290 --> 00:26:34.230 align:middle line:90%
with your own unique vibration.

00:26:34.230 --> 00:26:35.059 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Yes.

00:26:35.059 --> 00:26:36.100 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: You have that.

00:26:36.100 --> 00:26:37.380 align:middle line:90%
Nobody else does.

00:26:37.380 --> 00:26:39.150 align:middle line:90%
Nobody's heart sounds the same.

00:26:39.150 --> 00:26:40.990 align:middle line:90%
Nobody else's breath.

00:26:40.990 --> 00:26:43.050 align:middle line:90%
And you start to re-listen.

00:26:43.050 --> 00:26:44.390 align:middle line:90%
Wow, what is my passion?

00:26:44.390 --> 00:26:45.250 align:middle line:90%
What is my purpose?

00:26:45.250 --> 00:26:47.390 align:middle line:90%
What am I here to share?

00:26:47.390 --> 00:26:50.750 align:middle line:84%
Do it in your day
in five minutes when

00:26:50.750 --> 00:26:52.790 align:middle line:90%
you feel you need it.

00:26:52.790 --> 00:26:54.020 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Very centering.

00:26:54.020 --> 00:26:54.520 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Mm-hm.

00:26:54.520 --> 00:26:55.270 align:middle line:90%
Very centering.

00:26:55.270 --> 00:26:56.800 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: Well, how
about if we listen

00:26:56.800 --> 00:26:58.590 align:middle line:90%
to one of your pieces of music?

00:26:58.590 --> 00:27:00.110 align:middle line:84%
Since you're here,
it's the morning,

00:27:00.110 --> 00:27:02.820 align:middle line:84%
you've done your Sacred
Heartbeat Process, right?

00:27:02.820 --> 00:27:03.620 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Yes.

00:27:03.620 --> 00:27:06.203 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: And now we're going to
listen to a piece of music that

00:27:06.203 --> 00:27:08.470 align:middle line:84%
might accompany that, and
then once it comes up,

00:27:08.470 --> 00:27:10.540 align:middle line:90%
we'll be quiet for a little bit.

00:27:10.540 --> 00:27:14.270 align:middle line:84%
And then you can explain to us
why that particular piece, what

