And so this notion of music
as a bridge, in general,

00:36:10.590 --> 00:36:13.230 align:middle line:84%
was really kind of serving
that role for you two

00:36:13.230 --> 00:36:15.690 align:middle line:84%
to help you in the
recognition that this

00:36:15.690 --> 00:36:18.744 align:middle line:84%
is a beautiful compatible thing
that's just starting up here.

00:36:18.744 --> 00:36:19.660 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Absolutely.

00:36:19.660 --> 00:36:20.460 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:36:20.460 --> 00:36:22.810 align:middle line:84%
And you know, harmony
is not just a word that

00:36:22.810 --> 00:36:24.610 align:middle line:90%
exists in the musical language.

00:36:24.610 --> 00:36:27.420 align:middle line:84%
I always think of
music as a way of life.

00:36:27.420 --> 00:36:29.770 align:middle line:90%
So we're not the same note.

00:36:29.770 --> 00:36:31.152 align:middle line:90%
That would be boring.

00:36:31.152 --> 00:36:32.360 align:middle line:90%
But we complement each other.

00:36:32.360 --> 00:36:34.960 align:middle line:84%
We're in harmony
with each other,

00:36:34.960 --> 00:36:39.360 align:middle line:84%
and that's something that I go
to in-depth about in the book

00:36:39.360 --> 00:36:42.530 align:middle line:84%
as well is how to identify
who's creating harmony

00:36:42.530 --> 00:36:44.890 align:middle line:84%
and who's creating
dissonance in your field.

00:36:44.890 --> 00:36:45.690 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Right.

00:36:45.690 --> 00:36:46.920 align:middle line:90%
Talk about that.

00:36:46.920 --> 00:36:49.250 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: Well, when we're
creating an intention,

00:36:49.250 --> 00:36:51.180 align:middle line:90%
it's a very sacred thing.

00:36:51.180 --> 00:36:54.040 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes it's
between us and, call it

00:36:54.040 --> 00:36:57.740 align:middle line:84%
what you may-- spirit, God,
the universe, the divine.

00:36:57.740 --> 00:37:00.400 align:middle line:84%
When you have that intention,
and you are treating it

00:37:00.400 --> 00:37:02.520 align:middle line:84%
in a sacred way, who
do you want to bring

00:37:02.520 --> 00:37:04.920 align:middle line:90%
into that field with you?

00:37:04.920 --> 00:37:06.560 align:middle line:90%
It's a sacred field.

00:37:06.560 --> 00:37:10.540 align:middle line:84%
And as you start to introduce
people into that field,

00:37:10.540 --> 00:37:14.070 align:middle line:84%
you can see who is creating
dissonance in your field.

00:37:14.070 --> 00:37:18.350 align:middle line:84%
Who's saying, well, no, I
think that's not a great idea.

00:37:18.350 --> 00:37:22.340 align:middle line:84%
Puncturing holes, energetic
holes in your passion,

00:37:22.340 --> 00:37:24.250 align:middle line:84%
your purpose, what's
in your heart.

00:37:24.250 --> 00:37:25.050 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Right.

00:37:25.050 --> 00:37:28.490 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: So it's important
to recognize and build

00:37:28.490 --> 00:37:31.840 align:middle line:84%
harmonious spiritual
relationships

00:37:31.840 --> 00:37:35.460 align:middle line:84%
and a spiritual team around
you that supports your vision

00:37:35.460 --> 00:37:38.860 align:middle line:84%
and to be an observer
and an astute awareness,

00:37:38.860 --> 00:37:41.910 align:middle line:84%
and listen to who
is creating harmony

00:37:41.910 --> 00:37:44.440 align:middle line:84%
and who is creating
dissonance in your field.

00:37:44.440 --> 00:37:46.400 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: And you mentioned
this earlier, too.

00:37:46.400 --> 00:37:51.920 align:middle line:84%
When you're choosing your music,
whatever time of the day it is,

00:37:51.920 --> 00:37:54.850 align:middle line:84%
for whatever purpose,
you're really

00:37:54.850 --> 00:37:58.300 align:middle line:84%
looking for music that
creates a sense of expansion,

00:37:58.300 --> 00:38:00.040 align:middle line:84%
where you can feel
your energy moving

00:38:00.040 --> 00:38:04.270 align:middle line:84%
outward, more embracing, more
extended, versus contraction.

00:38:04.270 --> 00:38:05.910 align:middle line:90%
Talk about this a little bit.

00:38:05.910 --> 00:38:06.710 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Yeah.

00:38:06.710 --> 00:38:08.570 align:middle line:84%
Well, contraction
is-- I compare it

00:38:08.570 --> 00:38:11.820 align:middle line:84%
to being like on a winter's day
when you're kind of like this,

00:38:11.820 --> 00:38:15.600 align:middle line:84%
and you're cold, and
you're moving inward.

00:38:15.600 --> 00:38:17.880 align:middle line:84%
Your body's tight,
and you're stressed.

00:38:17.880 --> 00:38:20.160 align:middle line:84%
Expansion, I
compare-- and you'll

00:38:20.160 --> 00:38:22.750 align:middle line:84%
love this-- being
on top of a mountain

00:38:22.750 --> 00:38:27.120 align:middle line:84%
and being like this, wide
open, feeling like a speck

00:38:27.120 --> 00:38:30.260 align:middle line:84%
in the universe, but
like anything can happen.

00:38:30.260 --> 00:38:34.580 align:middle line:84%
So usually during our day, we'll
start off in an expansive way,

00:38:34.580 --> 00:38:35.900 align:middle line:90%
but things come into our field.

00:38:35.900 --> 00:38:38.890 align:middle line:84%
Challenges come in, whether
you're working with people

00:38:38.890 --> 00:38:43.060 align:middle line:84%
or you're a doctor working with
patients, whatever that is.

00:38:43.060 --> 00:38:46.340 align:middle line:84%
And we can move back into
that contracted state.

00:38:46.340 --> 00:38:50.900 align:middle line:84%
Music is an amazing way to move
back into the expansive state

00:38:50.900 --> 00:38:51.700 align:middle line:90%
again.

00:38:51.700 --> 00:38:54.300 align:middle line:84%
So asking yourself, what's
going to create expansion for me

00:38:54.300 --> 00:38:55.300 align:middle line:90%
right now?

00:38:55.300 --> 00:38:58.330 align:middle line:84%
Because for me, we don't
only have so much energy

00:38:58.330 --> 00:39:03.650 align:middle line:84%
that we can spend and find our
purpose and our passion with.

00:39:03.650 --> 00:39:06.370 align:middle line:84%
And if we're spending
it in states of drama

00:39:06.370 --> 00:39:08.810 align:middle line:84%
or spending it in those
contracted states,

00:39:08.810 --> 00:39:11.809 align:middle line:84%
then we have nothing left
for what we're here to do.

00:39:11.809 --> 00:39:12.850 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: That's very true.

00:39:12.850 --> 00:39:16.450 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: And so that piece
of music is a reconnection,

00:39:16.450 --> 00:39:19.440 align:middle line:84%
where you can move into that
expansive state, ask yourself,

00:39:19.440 --> 00:39:21.250 align:middle line:90%
what am I here for today?

00:39:21.250 --> 00:39:23.320 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: So practically
speaking, it's

00:39:23.320 --> 00:39:25.360 align:middle line:84%
a really smart
idea for each of us

00:39:25.360 --> 00:39:28.640 align:middle line:84%
to have our own personalized
preferred playlist,

00:39:28.640 --> 00:39:32.940 align:middle line:84%
our happy song, our
inspirational song,

00:39:32.940 --> 00:39:35.490 align:middle line:84%
our songs that make
us feel expansive

00:39:35.490 --> 00:39:37.100 align:middle line:90%
after we've just contracted.

00:39:37.100 --> 00:39:39.840 align:middle line:84%
I mean is there any
music that really-- I

00:39:39.840 --> 00:39:42.320 align:middle line:84%
mean one could say just
by way of preference--

00:39:42.320 --> 00:39:44.710 align:middle line:90%
really contracts you?

00:39:44.710 --> 00:39:48.015 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: Well, I mean I'm sure
people have listened to songs

00:39:48.015 --> 00:39:49.260 align:middle line:90%
and say, shut that off.

00:39:49.260 --> 00:39:50.100 align:middle line:90%
Turn that down.

00:39:50.100 --> 00:39:50.900 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Yeah.

00:39:50.900 --> 00:39:52.520 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: And that's
where we, again,

00:39:52.520 --> 00:39:56.080 align:middle line:84%
we become our own experts of
what feels good for us and what

00:39:56.080 --> 00:39:56.880 align:middle line:90%
doesn't.

00:39:56.880 --> 00:39:59.350 align:middle line:84%
And I think with the
technology and having access

00:39:59.350 --> 00:40:02.860 align:middle line:84%
to so many different
types of music that we now

00:40:02.860 --> 00:40:06.020 align:middle line:84%
have the ability to take
it to the next level

00:40:06.020 --> 00:40:10.757 align:middle line:84%
with our playlists and
target specific states.

00:40:10.757 --> 00:40:12.590 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: No, I think
that's a wonderful idea.

00:40:12.590 --> 00:40:13.465 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Gratitude.

00:40:13.465 --> 00:40:17.940 align:middle line:84%
A playlist for gratitude,
a playlist for inspiration,

00:40:17.940 --> 00:40:22.010 align:middle line:84%
a playlist for sensuality,
for all those as opposed

00:40:22.010 --> 00:40:24.110 align:middle line:84%
to a day at the beach
or reggae music.

00:40:24.110 --> 00:40:26.470 align:middle line:84%
They're great, but let's
bump it up a notch.

00:40:26.470 --> 00:40:28.600 align:middle line:84%
Let's bring the
awareness up, and know

00:40:28.600 --> 00:40:31.460 align:middle line:84%
that we all have the ability
to be the DJs of our own lives.

00:40:31.460 --> 00:40:32.260 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Right.

00:40:32.260 --> 00:40:33.760 align:middle line:84%
No, I think that's
a wonderful idea.

00:40:33.760 --> 00:40:35.240 align:middle line:84%
I mean I have made
playlists that

00:40:35.240 --> 00:40:38.360 align:middle line:84%
are kind of emotion-oriented
like I made one called Queen

00:40:38.360 --> 00:40:41.159 align:middle line:90%
of Clean for cleaning house.

00:40:41.159 --> 00:40:42.450 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: I need to have that.

00:40:42.450 --> 00:40:43.575 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Every single upper.

00:40:43.575 --> 00:40:44.930 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, let's do this.

00:40:44.930 --> 00:40:46.890 align:middle line:84%
So I'd be bopping along
while I was cleaning.

00:40:46.890 --> 00:40:51.360 align:middle line:84%
And another one I called
Crybaby, the double entendre,

00:40:51.360 --> 00:40:56.025 align:middle line:84%
that was just emotionally
sensitive and even sad music.

00:40:56.025 --> 00:40:57.400 align:middle line:84%
But that's as far
as I've gotten.

00:40:57.400 --> 00:40:59.690 align:middle line:84%
But what you're talking
about for all of us,

00:40:59.690 --> 00:41:02.030 align:middle line:84%
I mean I think everyone
listening, why wouldn't we

00:41:02.030 --> 00:41:05.360 align:middle line:84%
create our inspiration
list, our peaceful list,

00:41:05.360 --> 00:41:06.630 align:middle line:90%
our motivating list?

00:41:06.630 --> 00:41:07.700 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Absolutely.

00:41:07.700 --> 00:41:10.710 align:middle line:84%
You know, it's
musical nourishment.

00:41:10.710 --> 00:41:14.610 align:middle line:84%
It's just like we know that
meditation is great for us.

00:41:14.610 --> 00:41:16.480 align:middle line:84%
We know that eating
a certain way

00:41:16.480 --> 00:41:18.140 align:middle line:90%
is going to benefit our health.

00:41:18.140 --> 00:41:21.790 align:middle line:84%
We know music creates
transformation for us,

00:41:21.790 --> 00:41:23.820 align:middle line:84%
but most of the
time, it's random.

00:41:23.820 --> 00:41:26.710 align:middle line:84%
We let those pieces
happen to us randomly.

00:41:26.710 --> 00:41:29.930 align:middle line:84%
But what happens when you
start to drive that vehicle?

00:41:29.930 --> 00:41:35.890 align:middle line:84%
And you become the person who is
creating a practice around it.

00:41:35.890 --> 00:41:40.730 align:middle line:84%
It has the same benefits as
nourishment, as meditation.

00:41:40.730 --> 00:41:42.300 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: So on that
note, let's listen

00:41:42.300 --> 00:41:43.591 align:middle line:90%
to another piece of your music.

00:41:43.591 --> 00:41:45.220 align:middle line:90%
This is more for midday, right?

00:41:45.220 --> 00:41:45.680 align:middle line:90%
This is called--

00:41:45.680 --> 00:41:46.000 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Yes.

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:46.940 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: Is it
"Abundance Rising?"

00:41:46.940 --> 00:41:47.620 align:middle line:90%
Is that the name of it?

00:41:47.620 --> 00:41:48.410 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: This is called
"Abundance Rising."

00:41:48.410 --> 00:41:50.040 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: "Abundance
Rising," and let's just

00:41:50.040 --> 00:41:51.300 align:middle line:90%
listen to it for a little bit.

00:41:51.300 --> 00:41:54.030 align:middle line:84%
This one, we won't be as tempted
to go under like last time.

00:41:54.030 --> 00:41:55.060 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: No, we'll
feel ready to go.

00:41:55.060 --> 00:41:55.310 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: OK.

00:41:55.310 --> 00:41:57.330 align:middle line:84%
We're taking it in a
little bit, because it

00:41:57.330 --> 00:41:58.962 align:middle line:84%
has a ramp-up to
this, so we're going

00:41:58.962 --> 00:42:00.170 align:middle line:90%
to take it in about a minute.

00:42:00.170 --> 00:42:00.970 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:42:00.970 --> 00:42:02.224 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Sounds good.

