00:42:06.697 --> 00:42:45.470 align:middle line:90%


00:42:45.470 --> 00:42:47.540 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: So that starts
ramping up the mojo.

00:42:47.540 --> 00:42:49.830 align:middle line:84%
If you've kind of
lost your steam,

00:42:49.830 --> 00:42:53.010 align:middle line:84%
it has an inspirational quality
to it as well, I notice.

00:42:53.010 --> 00:42:55.750 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: It does, and it has
a lot of nice, low grounding

00:42:55.750 --> 00:42:57.140 align:middle line:90%
frequencies in there.

00:42:57.140 --> 00:42:59.740 align:middle line:84%
But it also has
Gregorian chantings,

00:42:59.740 --> 00:43:01.810 align:middle line:84%
so it brings in the
heavenly aspects.

00:43:01.810 --> 00:43:04.270 align:middle line:84%
It has some hip hop beats
in the middle of it,

00:43:04.270 --> 00:43:06.180 align:middle line:84%
so it's a little
bit more modern.

00:43:06.180 --> 00:43:09.740 align:middle line:84%
And it's great to work with
breathing and releasing energy

00:43:09.740 --> 00:43:12.610 align:middle line:84%
that you're holding
in your physical body.

00:43:12.610 --> 00:43:15.140 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: And you know, how
systems such as Hemi-Sync

00:43:15.140 --> 00:43:19.110 align:middle line:84%
and others have been created
that use these basic beats

00:43:19.110 --> 00:43:22.350 align:middle line:84%
and binaural beats and so
forth to kind of subconsciously

00:43:22.350 --> 00:43:23.150 align:middle line:90%
affect the brain.

00:43:23.150 --> 00:43:26.244 align:middle line:84%
But as we've learned, I mean
it's not a one size fits all.

00:43:26.244 --> 00:43:27.910 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: It's not
a one size fits all,

00:43:27.910 --> 00:43:30.420 align:middle line:84%
and I think that's
important as well.

00:43:30.420 --> 00:43:34.260 align:middle line:84%
When we're talking about
using music as medicine,

00:43:34.260 --> 00:43:35.830 align:middle line:84%
that we have to
think of it that way,

00:43:35.830 --> 00:43:39.100 align:middle line:84%
that each person is like a
patient that we're treating.

00:43:39.100 --> 00:43:40.750 align:middle line:90%
They're individual.

00:43:40.750 --> 00:43:43.250 align:middle line:84%
And what might
work for one person

00:43:43.250 --> 00:43:45.040 align:middle line:90%
might not work for the other.

00:43:45.040 --> 00:43:49.970 align:middle line:84%
And the music, I feel, at some
times, gets negated in the talk

00:43:49.970 --> 00:43:54.190 align:middle line:84%
about that, because it's very
much about the composition

00:43:54.190 --> 00:43:55.040 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:43:55.040 --> 00:43:56.739 align:middle line:90%
It's not just the technology.

00:43:56.739 --> 00:43:58.030 align:middle line:90%
You know, it's the composition.

00:43:58.030 --> 00:43:58.700 align:middle line:90%
It's the emotion.

00:43:58.700 --> 00:44:00.250 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: And you're getting
the intention of the composer.

00:44:00.250 --> 00:44:00.820 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Exactly.

00:44:00.820 --> 00:44:02.210 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: And the emotion
of the composer.

00:44:02.210 --> 00:44:03.168 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: All of that.

00:44:03.168 --> 00:44:05.780 align:middle line:84%
So when you combine
all of that together,

00:44:05.780 --> 00:44:10.560 align:middle line:84%
that's going to have a
powerful effect on the listener

00:44:10.560 --> 00:44:12.310 align:middle line:84%
if it's something that
they resonate with.

00:44:12.310 --> 00:44:15.040 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: We talked about this
off camera, because every now

00:44:15.040 --> 00:44:16.790 align:middle line:84%
and then, there's a
song that comes along,

00:44:16.790 --> 00:44:20.380 align:middle line:84%
and it may be the one hit
of that particular recording

00:44:20.380 --> 00:44:21.210 align:middle line:90%
artist.

00:44:21.210 --> 00:44:25.600 align:middle line:84%
But it comes along, and it
hits such a chord in everybody

00:44:25.600 --> 00:44:28.780 align:middle line:84%
that it becomes like an
overnight hit really.

00:44:28.780 --> 00:44:30.420 align:middle line:84%
And they can kind
of hang their hat

00:44:30.420 --> 00:44:32.810 align:middle line:84%
on that for the
rest of their lives.

00:44:32.810 --> 00:44:36.330 align:middle line:84%
Well, in the old days anyway
with royalties and performances

00:44:36.330 --> 00:44:37.130 align:middle line:90%
and so forth.

00:44:37.130 --> 00:44:40.670 align:middle line:84%
What is it that's happening
with that one song

00:44:40.670 --> 00:44:44.044 align:middle line:84%
that kind of everybody
seems to relate to?

00:44:44.044 --> 00:44:46.710 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: Well, I have a theory
that I love-- my background was

00:44:46.710 --> 00:44:51.730 align:middle line:84%
in pop music originally, so I'm
a person who studied pop music.

00:44:51.730 --> 00:44:54.030 align:middle line:84%
I feel that music
has always been

00:44:54.030 --> 00:44:58.100 align:middle line:84%
a representative of what
is happening culturally

00:44:58.100 --> 00:44:59.700 align:middle line:90%
in our society.

00:44:59.700 --> 00:45:04.650 align:middle line:84%
So I'm sure for people who are
listening to more modern music,

00:45:04.650 --> 00:45:07.130 align:middle line:84%
if they listen to Bob Dylan,
"Blowing in the Wind,"

00:45:07.130 --> 00:45:10.780 align:middle line:84%
they might not think that's a
great song or like his voice.

00:45:10.780 --> 00:45:13.970 align:middle line:84%
But at that time, that was one
of the most powerful songs,

00:45:13.970 --> 00:45:17.400 align:middle line:84%
because it captured what
was going on in our country.

00:45:17.400 --> 00:45:21.220 align:middle line:84%
And I feel it's the same
thing when you look at artists

00:45:21.220 --> 00:45:23.170 align:middle line:90%
like Alanis Morissette.

00:45:23.170 --> 00:45:27.590 align:middle line:84%
She was turned down by lots
of different record labels,

00:45:27.590 --> 00:45:34.200 align:middle line:84%
and she hit a common chord that
hit about 23 million people

00:45:34.200 --> 00:45:36.210 align:middle line:90%
when that album came out.

00:45:36.210 --> 00:45:41.130 align:middle line:84%
And when the song, "You
Ought to Know," came out,

00:45:41.130 --> 00:45:43.930 align:middle line:84%
it was expressing an
angst to the relationship

00:45:43.930 --> 00:45:45.570 align:middle line:90%
that she was in.

00:45:45.570 --> 00:45:47.300 align:middle line:84%
"I want to remind
you of the mess

00:45:47.300 --> 00:45:49.170 align:middle line:90%
you made when you went away."

00:45:49.170 --> 00:45:50.010 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Right.

00:45:50.010 --> 00:45:51.660 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: And I
think it hit a chord

00:45:51.660 --> 00:45:57.770 align:middle line:84%
with women in that time period
that it's OK to express angst.

00:45:57.770 --> 00:46:01.270 align:middle line:84%
And the music was so
cathartic to do that.

00:46:01.270 --> 00:46:03.120 align:middle line:84%
Music was a vehicle,
so I feel like we

00:46:03.120 --> 00:46:06.492 align:middle line:84%
liberated all this energy that
was going on in our society.

00:46:06.492 --> 00:46:07.950 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: Trying to
manage it, trying

00:46:07.950 --> 00:46:11.690 align:middle line:84%
to manage the stress of a
tough relationship situation.

00:46:11.690 --> 00:46:12.490 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Yeah.

00:46:12.490 --> 00:46:17.090 align:middle line:84%
We taught them to push that
down, and you don't say that.

00:46:17.090 --> 00:46:22.130 align:middle line:84%
So here's a song that gives
people permission to say it.

00:46:22.130 --> 00:46:25.090 align:middle line:90%
And 23 million people said it.

00:46:25.090 --> 00:46:27.560 align:middle line:84%
And she won five
Grammys for that.

00:46:27.560 --> 00:46:29.530 align:middle line:84%
So it's an inspiration
to artists, too,

00:46:29.530 --> 00:46:35.500 align:middle line:84%
who have a voice out there that
always follow your inspiration.

00:46:35.500 --> 00:46:38.020 align:middle line:84%
Follow your heart
to get it out there,

00:46:38.020 --> 00:46:41.100 align:middle line:84%
because your voice is
needed out there now.

00:46:41.100 --> 00:46:41.980 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: And it does.

00:46:41.980 --> 00:46:45.370 align:middle line:84%
Its drives our emotions
that may be hidden,

00:46:45.370 --> 00:46:48.410 align:middle line:84%
like you said, and/or
filled with longing.

00:46:48.410 --> 00:46:50.530 align:middle line:84%
And as you said earlier
too, sometimes it's

00:46:50.530 --> 00:46:53.280 align:middle line:84%
just the pure emotional
state the artist was

00:46:53.280 --> 00:46:54.900 align:middle line:90%
in when they created the song.

00:46:54.900 --> 00:46:56.960 align:middle line:84%
Their heart is coming
through to all of us,

00:46:56.960 --> 00:46:59.930 align:middle line:84%
and our heart is going
into resonance with them

00:46:59.930 --> 00:47:01.360 align:middle line:90%
in pain or pleasure.

00:47:01.360 --> 00:47:02.160 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Right.

00:47:02.160 --> 00:47:04.190 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, and with
that, it was like,

00:47:04.190 --> 00:47:06.459 align:middle line:84%
yeah, you could feel
that in those songs.

00:47:06.459 --> 00:47:08.750 align:middle line:84%
And then on the other end,
right around that same time,

00:47:08.750 --> 00:47:09.950 align:middle line:90%
you had Sarah McLachlan--

00:47:09.950 --> 00:47:10.750 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Yes.

00:47:10.750 --> 00:47:13.570 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: --who wrote a
beautiful song called "Angel."

00:47:13.570 --> 00:47:14.670 align:middle line:90%
And you could feel that.

00:47:14.670 --> 00:47:15.620 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Right.

00:47:15.620 --> 00:47:19.460 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: So it really
covers a spectrum

00:47:19.460 --> 00:47:23.347 align:middle line:84%
of hitting a common chord of
what people need at that time.

00:47:23.347 --> 00:47:24.930 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: Well, let's
talk about chords,

00:47:24.930 --> 00:47:27.205 align:middle line:84%
because when we get
into it technically,

00:47:27.205 --> 00:47:30.400 align:middle line:84%
do you find that people
tend to either be

00:47:30.400 --> 00:47:36.350 align:middle line:84%
aligned more disposition-wise
with major versus minor chords?

00:47:36.350 --> 00:47:38.500 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: Well, I mean
they have a purpose.

00:47:38.500 --> 00:47:40.300 align:middle line:84%
So major chords are
going to connect us

00:47:40.300 --> 00:47:45.110 align:middle line:84%
more in a positive or
uplifting way at times.

00:47:45.110 --> 00:47:48.430 align:middle line:84%
And then minor chords make
us feel a little bit more sad

00:47:48.430 --> 00:47:50.310 align:middle line:90%
or a little bit more sallow.

00:47:50.310 --> 00:47:54.207 align:middle line:84%
So composers know these things
when we're creating songs.

00:47:54.207 --> 00:47:56.540 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: And it's the contrast
between the two in a song.

00:47:56.540 --> 00:47:56.780 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: That's right.

00:47:56.780 --> 00:47:58.590 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes we'll go
between major and minor,

00:47:58.590 --> 00:48:01.300 align:middle line:84%
and sometimes we'll
stay in a neutral place

00:48:01.300 --> 00:48:03.670 align:middle line:90%
and just have a drone.

00:48:03.670 --> 00:48:04.930 align:middle line:90%
It's all for a purpose.

00:48:04.930 --> 00:48:07.030 align:middle line:84%
Or sometimes we'll have
a point in a song, where

00:48:07.030 --> 00:48:09.110 align:middle line:90%
it's completely quiet.

00:48:09.110 --> 00:48:12.130 align:middle line:84%
And there are studies that
show that during those times

00:48:12.130 --> 00:48:16.320 align:middle line:84%
where there is silence, that's
when our attention is caught

00:48:16.320 --> 00:48:17.890 align:middle line:90%
even more so from the listener.

00:48:17.890 --> 00:48:18.250 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Yes.

00:48:18.250 --> 00:48:18.860 align:middle line:90%
I can see that.

00:48:18.860 --> 00:48:20.526 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: --And
improves our attention.

00:48:20.526 --> 00:48:21.740 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Right.

00:48:21.740 --> 00:48:24.360 align:middle line:84%
But I mean, thank
you for that answer.

00:48:24.360 --> 00:48:27.100 align:middle line:84%
I'm just wondering, have you
known-- I mean have you known--

00:48:27.100 --> 00:48:29.320 align:middle line:84%
can you tell whether
a person is generally

00:48:29.320 --> 00:48:31.700 align:middle line:84%
the kind that will prefer
major chords to minor chords,

00:48:31.700 --> 00:48:32.500 align:middle line:90%
for example?

00:48:32.500 --> 00:48:34.135 align:middle line:90%
Like "Rainy Day People."

00:48:34.135 --> 00:48:34.935 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Yeah.

00:48:34.935 --> 00:48:37.600 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: Are comforted
by minor chords often.

00:48:37.600 --> 00:48:41.190 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: Again, I think
that is where you're at

00:48:41.190 --> 00:48:43.200 align:middle line:90%
and where you want to go.

00:48:43.200 --> 00:48:46.970 align:middle line:84%
And also, certain things benefit
certain medical things as well,

00:48:46.970 --> 00:48:50.770 align:middle line:84%
like when I'm composing music
for sleeping challenges,

00:48:50.770 --> 00:48:52.870 align:middle line:84%
I try to stay in
between the two.

00:48:52.870 --> 00:48:55.610 align:middle line:84%
And I'm playing
what's called fifths.

00:48:55.610 --> 00:48:57.760 align:middle line:84%
So those outside
notes are not defining

00:48:57.760 --> 00:48:59.040 align:middle line:90%
whether it's major or minor.

00:48:59.040 --> 00:49:01.400 align:middle line:84%
It's the middle note
that defines that.

00:49:01.400 --> 00:49:03.770 align:middle line:84%
And I try to stay in between,
so I don't take people

00:49:03.770 --> 00:49:05.710 align:middle line:90%
to emotional states.

00:49:05.710 --> 00:49:07.970 align:middle line:84%
It's more like lighting
a candle in a room right

00:49:07.970 --> 00:49:09.220 align:middle line:90%
before you go to bed.

00:49:09.220 --> 00:49:10.830 align:middle line:84%
You don't want a
lot of distractions.

00:49:10.830 --> 00:49:12.770 align:middle line:84%
You don't want to
listen to a song

00:49:12.770 --> 00:49:14.500 align:middle line:84%
and say, oh, this
is my favorite part.

00:49:14.500 --> 00:49:14.770 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Right.

00:49:14.770 --> 00:49:15.860 align:middle line:90%
Because now you're alert.

00:49:15.860 --> 00:49:16.760 align:middle line:90%
You're paying attention.

00:49:16.760 --> 00:49:17.720 align:middle line:90%
Your mind's active again.

00:49:17.720 --> 00:49:18.210 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Your mind's active.

00:49:18.210 --> 00:49:19.550 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Right.

00:49:19.550 --> 00:49:23.939 align:middle line:84%
Which of your CDs--
what's the name of your CD

00:49:23.939 --> 00:49:24.980 align:middle line:90%
that has to do with this?

00:49:24.980 --> 00:49:28.160 align:middle line:84%
Because I know someone right
now who's just having real sleep

00:49:28.160 --> 00:49:28.960 align:middle line:90%
issues.

00:49:28.960 --> 00:49:32.830 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: Yeah, so for
that, my series, "Ambiology,"

00:49:32.830 --> 00:49:35.650 align:middle line:90%
has a CD called "Genesis."

00:49:35.650 --> 00:49:40.075 align:middle line:84%
And "Genesis" has been used
clinically for insomnia and--

00:49:40.075 --> 00:49:41.600 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: In sleep clinics?

00:49:41.600 --> 00:49:45.030 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: Well, Dr.
Worden, Donese has used it,

00:49:45.030 --> 00:49:47.020 align:middle line:90%
and we're also studying it.

00:49:47.020 --> 00:49:48.810 align:middle line:84%
It's also been used
in hospitals as well

00:49:48.810 --> 00:49:49.810 align:middle line:90%
for sleeping challenges.

00:49:49.810 --> 00:49:50.420 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Does it work?

00:49:50.420 --> 00:49:51.350 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Oh, yeah.

00:49:51.350 --> 00:49:54.110 align:middle line:84%
Because it brings you to that
relaxed state very quickly.

00:49:54.110 --> 00:49:57.040 align:middle line:84%
It brings you down to
that 60 beats per minute.

00:49:57.040 --> 00:49:59.410 align:middle line:84%
And I always recommend
that when people

00:49:59.410 --> 00:50:03.010 align:middle line:84%
have sleeping challenges, when
you're using music for that,

00:50:03.010 --> 00:50:05.860 align:middle line:84%
it's not just about
putting it on before five

00:50:05.860 --> 00:50:08.160 align:middle line:90%
minutes before you go to sleep.

00:50:08.160 --> 00:50:10.330 align:middle line:84%
It's about winding
down and transitioning,

00:50:10.330 --> 00:50:12.630 align:middle line:84%
because so many of us
are going from type A--

00:50:12.630 --> 00:50:13.880 align:middle line:90%
we're on the internet.

00:50:13.880 --> 00:50:14.680 align:middle line:90%
Oh, my god.

00:50:14.680 --> 00:50:15.600 align:middle line:90%
It's 2 o'clock in the morning.

00:50:15.600 --> 00:50:16.516 align:middle line:90%
I need to go to sleep.

00:50:16.516 --> 00:50:17.320 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Now.

00:50:17.320 --> 00:50:17.880 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Right.

00:50:17.880 --> 00:50:18.700 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:50:18.700 --> 00:50:21.590 align:middle line:84%
To actually wind down,
start treating sleep

00:50:21.590 --> 00:50:25.320 align:middle line:84%
as a more sacred time, put
on that music about an hour

00:50:25.320 --> 00:50:29.160 align:middle line:84%
before bed time, and your
body starts to adapt to that.

00:50:29.160 --> 00:50:31.920 align:middle line:84%
So it took awhile for
you to move out of sync.

00:50:31.920 --> 00:50:35.820 align:middle line:84%
Give yourself at least 30
days to play that music

00:50:35.820 --> 00:50:37.700 align:middle line:84%
and to wind down
before sleep with it.

00:50:37.700 --> 00:50:40.750 align:middle line:84%
And you'll see that you're
staying asleep longer.

00:50:40.750 --> 00:50:42.450 align:middle line:84%
You're getting
better quality sleep.

00:50:42.450 --> 00:50:43.250 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: OK.

00:50:43.250 --> 00:50:46.820 align:middle line:84%
On that note, no pun intended,
let's take a listen to one more

00:50:46.820 --> 00:50:47.720 align:middle line:90%
piece of your music.

00:50:47.720 --> 00:50:50.700 align:middle line:84%
And this is for winding down
at the end of the day called

00:50:50.700 --> 00:50:51.740 align:middle line:90%
"Alpha Evening."

00:50:51.740 --> 00:50:52.280 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: That's correct.

00:50:52.280 --> 00:50:53.138 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: OK.

00:50:53.138 --> 00:50:57.122 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:50:57.122 --> 00:51:52.950 align:middle line:90%


00:51:52.950 --> 00:51:55.990 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: You can really hear
it bringing it down, quieting

00:51:55.990 --> 00:51:56.986 align:middle line:90%
everything in this.

00:51:56.986 --> 00:51:58.360 align:middle line:84%
And I would think
that that would

00:51:58.360 --> 00:52:02.530 align:middle line:84%
be, for a number of reasons,
a really lovely thing

00:52:02.530 --> 00:52:06.240 align:middle line:84%
for a couple to do-- to go to
bed earlier than you would.

00:52:06.240 --> 00:52:09.080 align:middle line:84%
Don't just turn off the
computer and try to crash.

00:52:09.080 --> 00:52:11.860 align:middle line:84%
But go to bed earlier,
and listen to music

00:52:11.860 --> 00:52:15.440 align:middle line:84%
together so that you fall
in a resonance together

00:52:15.440 --> 00:52:17.099 align:middle line:90%
and dream time together.

00:52:17.099 --> 00:52:18.390 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: That's a great idea.

00:52:18.390 --> 00:52:21.360 align:middle line:84%
I totally, totally
agree with you.

00:52:21.360 --> 00:52:24.330 align:middle line:84%
And you know, again,
it's about moving

00:52:24.330 --> 00:52:27.880 align:middle line:84%
into that parasympathetic
state, slowing your body down,

00:52:27.880 --> 00:52:30.890 align:middle line:84%
allowing it to
rest and rejuvenate

00:52:30.890 --> 00:52:34.000 align:middle line:84%
so that you could wake up in
that state, where you can share

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:36.120 align:middle line:90%
your passion and your purpose.

00:52:36.120 --> 00:52:36.977 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Right.

00:52:36.977 --> 00:52:38.560 align:middle line:84%
Well, let's talk--
we're going to-- we

00:52:38.560 --> 00:52:40.870 align:middle line:84%
have some time to still go
into a few other elements.

00:52:40.870 --> 00:52:44.580 align:middle line:84%
And one is toning and
what kind of part toning

00:52:44.580 --> 00:52:46.170 align:middle line:90%
plays in all of this.

00:52:46.170 --> 00:52:49.050 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: So for
toning, I like to tone

00:52:49.050 --> 00:52:51.310 align:middle line:84%
through parts of my
body that feel tense

00:52:51.310 --> 00:52:56.210 align:middle line:84%
or feel like they need
to release energy.

00:52:56.210 --> 00:52:58.620 align:middle line:84%
And I work through
the energy centers,

00:52:58.620 --> 00:53:02.090 align:middle line:84%
sending different
tones to those centers.

00:53:02.090 --> 00:53:04.300 align:middle line:84%
So your tone might be
slightly different than mine,

00:53:04.300 --> 00:53:08.460 align:middle line:84%
and it's really about
placing your hands on each

00:53:08.460 --> 00:53:12.330 align:middle line:84%
of your energy centers, and
we start with the base, which

00:53:12.330 --> 00:53:13.800 align:middle line:90%
is the base of our spine.

00:53:13.800 --> 00:53:17.460 align:middle line:84%
Within that center, I usually
send the lowest possible sound

00:53:17.460 --> 00:53:21.500 align:middle line:84%
that I can of U. And
so in the root chakra,

00:53:21.500 --> 00:53:23.730 align:middle line:84%
I send something
that would sound

00:53:23.730 --> 00:53:25.840 align:middle line:90%
like this with a big breath in.

00:53:25.840 --> 00:53:29.933 align:middle line:84%
[INHALES] I put my hand
on there, and then I go,

00:53:29.933 --> 00:53:41.037 align:middle line:90%
[LONG, DEEP VOICE] U.

00:53:41.037 --> 00:53:42.870 align:middle line:84%
So what I'm doing when
I'm doing that is I'm

00:53:42.870 --> 00:53:45.470 align:middle line:84%
searching for that
sound that feels

00:53:45.470 --> 00:53:47.070 align:middle line:90%
like it's vibrating my hand.

00:53:47.070 --> 00:53:48.450 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: Right, and breaking
up an old energy pattern

00:53:48.450 --> 00:53:49.474 align:middle line:90%
that may be stuck there.

00:53:49.474 --> 00:53:50.390 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Absolutely.

00:53:50.390 --> 00:53:52.830 align:middle line:84%
And you can usually tell as
you go through your centers,

00:53:52.830 --> 00:53:57.600 align:middle line:84%
as you go up, each center
has a different sound

00:53:57.600 --> 00:53:59.270 align:middle line:84%
that you can feel
which ones, oh,

00:53:59.270 --> 00:54:02.640 align:middle line:84%
that one felt really open and
expansive as I tone through it.

00:54:02.640 --> 00:54:05.730 align:middle line:84%
That one I could hardly
get any sound through.

00:54:05.730 --> 00:54:07.980 align:middle line:84%
And as we work with
our energy centers,

00:54:07.980 --> 00:54:11.420 align:middle line:84%
there are areas that are geared
toward specific consciousness,

00:54:11.420 --> 00:54:13.670 align:middle line:84%
different aspects of
emotions, as you said,

00:54:13.670 --> 00:54:14.980 align:middle line:90%
that we hold there.

00:54:14.980 --> 00:54:17.670 align:middle line:84%
So as you see which
ones are blocked,

00:54:17.670 --> 00:54:21.760 align:middle line:84%
and you see what that
means-- for instance,

00:54:21.760 --> 00:54:25.440 align:middle line:84%
the throat is geared
towards expression,

00:54:25.440 --> 00:54:28.280 align:middle line:84%
knowing that your
words are heard,

00:54:28.280 --> 00:54:30.380 align:middle line:90%
acknowledged, and appreciated.

00:54:30.380 --> 00:54:33.030 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a hard time
toning through that throat

00:54:33.030 --> 00:54:35.490 align:middle line:84%
chakra, it could be
maybe something happened

00:54:35.490 --> 00:54:37.920 align:middle line:84%
at work, where you
didn't feel like you were

00:54:37.920 --> 00:54:39.440 align:middle line:84%
heard in that
moment, or you didn't

00:54:39.440 --> 00:54:42.130 align:middle line:90%
get to fully express yourself.

00:54:42.130 --> 00:54:45.580 align:middle line:84%
Within the third eye, it
could be a lot of mind chatter

00:54:45.580 --> 00:54:48.830 align:middle line:84%
that you've been locked into
a story that's been going on.

00:54:48.830 --> 00:54:51.840 align:middle line:84%
So when you start to realize
that each one of them

00:54:51.840 --> 00:54:55.380 align:middle line:84%
has something that is specific
emotionally that ties to it,

00:54:55.380 --> 00:54:57.420 align:middle line:84%
then we have the ability
to tone through it.

00:54:57.420 --> 00:55:00.950 align:middle line:84%
Work with the ones
that are blocked more,

00:55:00.950 --> 00:55:03.430 align:middle line:84%
and see if it does have
a resonance to something

00:55:03.430 --> 00:55:06.260 align:middle line:84%
that's going on
emotionally in your life,

00:55:06.260 --> 00:55:09.170 align:middle line:84%
because as soon as you do
that, you liberate energy.

00:55:09.170 --> 00:55:11.540 align:middle line:90%
You let energy go, and--

00:55:11.540 --> 00:55:13.210 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: Back to that
expansive state.

00:55:13.210 --> 00:55:13.480 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:55:13.480 --> 00:55:14.280 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Exactly.

00:55:14.280 --> 00:55:16.590 align:middle line:84%
You make room for more
energy to come in.

00:55:16.590 --> 00:55:20.260 align:middle line:84%
Now you've found yourself having
a lot of support in your life,

00:55:20.260 --> 00:55:24.270 align:middle line:84%
because you've cleared your base
chakra or a lot of nurturing,

00:55:24.270 --> 00:55:28.170 align:middle line:84%
or you feel like you're able
to walk more in your path.

00:55:28.170 --> 00:55:29.180 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Right.

00:55:29.180 --> 00:55:31.510 align:middle line:84%
Now when-- let's
talk about using

00:55:31.510 --> 00:55:34.655 align:middle line:84%
songs for a very specific
reason, because were talk

00:55:34.655 --> 00:55:37.920 align:middle line:84%
quite a bit in your book
about using songs to help

00:55:37.920 --> 00:55:40.440 align:middle line:90%
you set and keep an intention.

00:55:40.440 --> 00:55:41.814 align:middle line:90%
So let's get into that.

00:55:41.814 --> 00:55:42.730 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Absolutely.

00:55:42.730 --> 00:55:45.560 align:middle line:84%
So I think this is a
part that's usually

00:55:45.560 --> 00:55:48.160 align:middle line:84%
within the sound
healing community,

00:55:48.160 --> 00:55:53.160 align:middle line:84%
we don't talk about like
using popular new music a lot.

00:55:53.160 --> 00:55:56.170 align:middle line:84%
And I think that
popular music absolutely

00:55:56.170 --> 00:55:58.500 align:middle line:84%
can be healing as
well, especially

00:55:58.500 --> 00:56:00.490 align:middle line:90%
with creating intention.

00:56:00.490 --> 00:56:04.520 align:middle line:84%
This is where songs with
lyrics do assist you.

00:56:04.520 --> 00:56:07.520 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a
business meeting,

00:56:07.520 --> 00:56:09.240 align:middle line:84%
and you need to be
geared up, maybe

00:56:09.240 --> 00:56:11.110 align:middle line:84%
"I'm So Excited" by
the Pointer Sisters.

00:56:11.110 --> 00:56:11.660 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Oh, yeah.

00:56:11.660 --> 00:56:12.040 align:middle line:90%
Oh, yeah.

00:56:12.040 --> 00:56:12.910 align:middle line:90%
That's a good one.

00:56:12.910 --> 00:56:17.470 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: Or you're an
actress living in Iowa,

00:56:17.470 --> 00:56:21.640 align:middle line:84%
and you know that all your
acting jobs are going to happen

00:56:21.640 --> 00:56:23.310 align:middle line:90%
if you move to New York.

00:56:23.310 --> 00:56:25.470 align:middle line:84%
So you listen to Frank
Sinatra every day,

00:56:25.470 --> 00:56:27.080 align:middle line:84%
and you put yourself
in that space

00:56:27.080 --> 00:56:29.850 align:middle line:84%
of listening to "New York,
New York," smelling what

00:56:29.850 --> 00:56:33.330 align:middle line:84%
New York-- the sounds and
the smell of the pizza

00:56:33.330 --> 00:56:38.500 align:middle line:84%
coming out from the pizza
shops, and all of the atmosphere

00:56:38.500 --> 00:56:39.320 align:middle line:90%
there.

00:56:39.320 --> 00:56:43.020 align:middle line:84%
And you constantly use this
song to create a field that's

00:56:43.020 --> 00:56:46.820 align:middle line:84%
going to bring that
resonance and that attraction

00:56:46.820 --> 00:56:48.110 align:middle line:90%
into your life.

00:56:48.110 --> 00:56:51.650 align:middle line:84%
And as you move into those
elevated states of emotion,

00:56:51.650 --> 00:56:53.490 align:middle line:90%
that's when intention happens.

00:56:53.490 --> 00:56:55.270 align:middle line:84%
When you're combining
the intention

00:56:55.270 --> 00:56:56.750 align:middle line:90%
and the elevated emotion of--

00:56:56.750 --> 00:56:57.550 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Absolutely.

00:56:57.550 --> 00:57:00.860 align:middle line:84%
People-- that's the one that's
been difficult in the New Age

00:57:00.860 --> 00:57:04.450 align:middle line:84%
community in particular to
kind of break the notion

00:57:04.450 --> 00:57:06.550 align:middle line:84%
that all you have to
do is say, I want this,

00:57:06.550 --> 00:57:08.300 align:middle line:84%
and repeatedly it's
going to happen.

00:57:08.300 --> 00:57:12.510 align:middle line:84%
It's so inextricably intertwined
with the positive emotions

00:57:12.510 --> 00:57:15.560 align:middle line:90%
supporting that experience.

00:57:15.560 --> 00:57:16.660 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Exactly.

00:57:16.660 --> 00:57:18.690 align:middle line:84%
And this is where it moves
into being-- it could

00:57:18.690 --> 00:57:20.740 align:middle line:90%
be a quick fix in any area.

00:57:20.740 --> 00:57:22.880 align:middle line:84%
It could be a quick
fix in New Age,

00:57:22.880 --> 00:57:24.885 align:middle line:84%
just as it could be
in the medical arena.

00:57:24.885 --> 00:57:25.760 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Right, right.

00:57:25.760 --> 00:57:27.660 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: You know,
so for me, it always

00:57:27.660 --> 00:57:31.190 align:middle line:84%
comes back to, again,
what am I here to do?

00:57:31.190 --> 00:57:34.360 align:middle line:84%
How am I here to serve,
and what could put me back

00:57:34.360 --> 00:57:35.240 align:middle line:90%
on track to do that?

00:57:35.240 --> 00:57:36.040 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Right.

00:57:36.040 --> 00:57:38.610 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: What musical piece
can connect me with my heart,

00:57:38.610 --> 00:57:40.420 align:middle line:90%
which is going to speak to that?

00:57:40.420 --> 00:57:42.120 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: Well, and for
negative emotions,

00:57:42.120 --> 00:57:43.510 align:middle line:84%
if you want to
pull yourself out,

00:57:43.510 --> 00:57:45.030 align:middle line:84%
you like Bruce
Springsteen, right?

00:57:45.030 --> 00:57:45.830 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: I love--

00:57:45.830 --> 00:57:46.790 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: Did I read
that correctly?

00:57:46.790 --> 00:57:47.590 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Yeah.

00:57:47.590 --> 00:57:52.470 align:middle line:84%
I mean I love singing to
Bruce and releasing emotion

00:57:52.470 --> 00:57:56.360 align:middle line:84%
through songs like
"Jungleland" or "Born to Run."

00:57:56.360 --> 00:57:57.970 align:middle line:90%
And it brings me back.

00:57:57.970 --> 00:58:02.020 align:middle line:84%
It brings me back to my roots
of where this all started,

00:58:02.020 --> 00:58:03.850 align:middle line:90%
learning the power of music.

00:58:03.850 --> 00:58:07.240 align:middle line:84%
I think where I learned it
was in my park growing up

00:58:07.240 --> 00:58:09.990 align:middle line:84%
as each of my friends
would play a mix tape.

00:58:09.990 --> 00:58:11.600 align:middle line:84%
Back then, it was
cassette tapes.

00:58:11.600 --> 00:58:13.930 align:middle line:84%
And we'd have-- those
are our playlists.

00:58:13.930 --> 00:58:17.357 align:middle line:84%
We have a half an hour to share
what we love listening to.

00:58:17.357 --> 00:58:19.190 align:middle line:84%
And that's when I
realized like, oh, my god,

00:58:19.190 --> 00:58:22.610 align:middle line:84%
music shifted a friend
who was in depression.

00:58:22.610 --> 00:58:27.790 align:middle line:84%
Music shifted a friend who had
a gang member in his family, who

00:58:27.790 --> 00:58:29.290 align:middle line:90%
were coming home beaten up.

00:58:29.290 --> 00:58:33.910 align:middle line:84%
Music shifted my friends
who had alcoholic parents.

00:58:33.910 --> 00:58:36.422 align:middle line:84%
And I watched them shift
for those half an hour

00:58:36.422 --> 00:58:38.380 align:middle line:84%
into their own space,
where they were elevated.

00:58:38.380 --> 00:58:39.850 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: That's beautiful.

00:58:39.850 --> 00:58:40.160 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:58:40.160 --> 00:58:42.076 align:middle line:84%
And the thing is like
you said, you don't even

00:58:42.076 --> 00:58:44.730 align:middle line:84%
have to have whatever
your musical device is,

00:58:44.730 --> 00:58:48.030 align:middle line:84%
your iPod or your iPhone,
whatever, with you anymore.

00:58:48.030 --> 00:58:49.940 align:middle line:84%
All you have to do is
remember that song.

00:58:49.940 --> 00:58:50.570 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: That's right.

00:58:50.570 --> 00:58:52.403 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: As soon as you
remember it and start

00:58:52.403 --> 00:58:54.320 align:middle line:84%
going into it in your
head, it's starting

00:58:54.320 --> 00:58:56.930 align:middle line:84%
to have the same effect through
memory as it does to actually

00:58:56.930 --> 00:58:58.250 align:middle line:90%
listen to it on a device.

00:58:58.250 --> 00:58:59.249 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: That's right.

00:58:59.249 --> 00:59:01.420 align:middle line:84%
As I was just describing
that, I was in the park.

00:59:01.420 --> 00:59:03.520 align:middle line:84%
I was hanging out on
the bench listening.

00:59:03.520 --> 00:59:07.880 align:middle line:84%
I could see Joe's boombox
there and all of my friends.

00:59:07.880 --> 00:59:09.940 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: So for you,
another one when

00:59:09.940 --> 00:59:12.070 align:middle line:84%
you begin your day, one
of your favorite songs

00:59:12.070 --> 00:59:15.010 align:middle line:84%
is "Morning Has Broken"
by Cat Stevens, which

00:59:15.010 --> 00:59:16.750 align:middle line:90%
is just such a beautiful song.

00:59:16.750 --> 00:59:17.550 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: It is.

00:59:17.550 --> 00:59:18.400 align:middle line:90%
And you know what?

00:59:18.400 --> 00:59:21.850 align:middle line:90%
It connects us to nature.

00:59:21.850 --> 00:59:24.120 align:middle line:84%
It connects us to
the miracles that

00:59:24.120 --> 00:59:28.240 align:middle line:84%
are all around us that when we
start our day, that no matter

00:59:28.240 --> 00:59:30.080 align:middle line:84%
what's going on,
we have the ability

00:59:30.080 --> 00:59:32.290 align:middle line:84%
to tap into the
small things that

00:59:32.290 --> 00:59:33.780 align:middle line:84%
have been created
in the planets,

00:59:33.780 --> 00:59:35.910 align:middle line:90%
in the flowers, the birds.

00:59:35.910 --> 00:59:38.370 align:middle line:84%
And when we see
those small things,

00:59:38.370 --> 00:59:41.030 align:middle line:84%
and we're able to
connect with those,

00:59:41.030 --> 00:59:44.960 align:middle line:84%
then we move into that space
of gratitude of why we're here.

00:59:44.960 --> 00:59:48.680 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: Yes, and it is such a
kind of melodic little thing,

00:59:48.680 --> 00:59:49.750 align:middle line:90%
such a beautiful piece.

00:59:49.750 --> 00:59:52.340 align:middle line:84%
So we each need to find our
own version of "Morning Has

00:59:52.340 --> 00:59:53.410 align:middle line:90%
Broken."

00:59:53.410 --> 00:59:56.830 align:middle line:84%
A good way to start the day,
as you say, with gratitude.

00:59:56.830 --> 00:59:59.140 align:middle line:84%
And fortunately, you've
done the hard work

00:59:59.140 --> 01:00:01.960 align:middle line:84%
in that you created all
these different CDs that

01:00:01.960 --> 01:00:03.690 align:middle line:84%
have these different
compilations on them

01:00:03.690 --> 01:00:05.474 align:middle line:84%
that we can just
plug into as well.

01:00:05.474 --> 01:00:06.390 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Absolutely.

01:00:06.390 --> 01:00:07.190 align:middle line:90%
And it was great.

01:00:07.190 --> 01:00:09.200 align:middle line:84%
When you find out somebody
else's happy song,

01:00:09.200 --> 01:00:11.270 align:middle line:90%
then it becomes your happy song.

01:00:11.270 --> 01:00:12.070 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Yes.

01:00:12.070 --> 01:00:14.100 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: So it's a
community thing too

01:00:14.100 --> 01:00:16.679 align:middle line:90%
that we can all share as well.

01:00:16.679 --> 01:00:18.720 align:middle line:84%
Like I like "Kung Fu
Fighting" a lot more since--

01:00:18.720 --> 01:00:18.890 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Yeah.

01:00:18.890 --> 01:00:19.690 align:middle line:90%
You're right.

01:00:19.690 --> 01:00:22.355 align:middle line:84%
We all need to find out
our sweetie's happy song.

01:00:22.355 --> 01:00:23.750 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Exactly.

01:00:23.750 --> 01:00:25.960 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: We have just
a couple minutes left.

01:00:25.960 --> 01:00:30.410 align:middle line:84%
Any final comments on maybe some
of the work and experimentation

01:00:30.410 --> 01:00:32.560 align:middle line:84%
going on right now, more
in the science arena,

01:00:32.560 --> 01:00:35.540 align:middle line:84%
or just in what's coming
up with you and your music?

01:00:35.540 --> 01:00:36.340 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Yeah.

01:00:36.340 --> 01:00:37.140 align:middle line:90%
Well, both.

01:00:37.140 --> 01:00:40.610 align:middle line:84%
Where I think we can really
move forward in this field

01:00:40.610 --> 01:00:43.590 align:middle line:84%
is getting more specific
in our research.

01:00:43.590 --> 01:00:45.550 align:middle line:84%
And I think we
tend to lump things

01:00:45.550 --> 01:00:49.750 align:middle line:84%
into genres-- classical
music or rock music.

01:00:49.750 --> 01:00:51.250 align:middle line:84%
How many millions
of songs are there

01:00:51.250 --> 01:00:53.050 align:middle line:90%
in each of those categories?

01:00:53.050 --> 01:00:55.350 align:middle line:84%
So what my focus
is is let's begin

01:00:55.350 --> 01:00:57.600 align:middle line:90%
to focus on designer music.

01:00:57.600 --> 01:01:01.280 align:middle line:84%
This specific piece
has this frequency,

01:01:01.280 --> 01:01:03.370 align:middle line:90%
and let's see if it works.

01:01:03.370 --> 01:01:05.940 align:middle line:84%
Because we need more information
on what frequency works

01:01:05.940 --> 01:01:08.440 align:middle line:84%
to move beyond urban
legend that's out there,

01:01:08.440 --> 01:01:13.100 align:middle line:84%
and let's see what really
works in quantitative studies.

01:01:13.100 --> 01:01:16.870 align:middle line:84%
And then within my work,
I'm excited to announce

01:01:16.870 --> 01:01:21.270 align:middle line:84%
that I'm releasing a
series for pets and humans

01:01:21.270 --> 01:01:23.430 align:middle line:84%
to bond with together,
because I think animals--

01:01:23.430 --> 01:01:24.160 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Oh, interesting.

01:01:24.160 --> 01:01:24.640 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

01:01:24.640 --> 01:01:26.280 align:middle line:90%
They're very sensitive to music.

01:01:26.280 --> 01:01:27.695 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: Yes, and to us.

01:01:27.695 --> 01:01:28.040 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Us.

01:01:28.040 --> 01:01:28.590 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

01:01:28.590 --> 01:01:30.173 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: So creating
a program where

01:01:30.173 --> 01:01:31.969 align:middle line:90%
we connect with our animals.

01:01:31.969 --> 01:01:33.760 align:middle line:84%
And HeartMath has done
some initial studies

01:01:33.760 --> 01:01:36.820 align:middle line:84%
showing that when we're in that
space where we're connecting

01:01:36.820 --> 01:01:39.020 align:middle line:84%
with our animals, that
actually, our heart rate

01:01:39.020 --> 01:01:42.440 align:middle line:84%
variabilities move into a
space of coherence together.

01:01:42.440 --> 01:01:43.240 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Yes.

01:01:43.240 --> 01:01:45.880 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: So this is
going to be a series that

01:01:45.880 --> 01:01:50.250 align:middle line:84%
works with us listening,
taking time with our pets,

01:01:50.250 --> 01:01:51.610 align:middle line:90%
winding down.

01:01:51.610 --> 01:01:52.960 align:middle line:90%
They feel our energy.

01:01:52.960 --> 01:01:55.060 align:middle line:84%
We feel their
unconditional love.

01:01:55.060 --> 01:01:58.400 align:middle line:84%
And I composed it initially
for our dog, Woody,

01:01:58.400 --> 01:02:03.800 align:middle line:84%
who we saved from
the Humane Society,

01:02:03.800 --> 01:02:08.780 align:middle line:84%
and has been an instrumental
part as my teacher.

01:02:08.780 --> 01:02:10.150 align:middle line:90%
Pets teach us patience, right?

01:02:10.150 --> 01:02:10.950 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Yes.

01:02:10.950 --> 01:02:13.930 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: So that's where I'm
going and lots of new projects

01:02:13.930 --> 01:02:17.520 align:middle line:84%
with great speakers and
supporting their work.

01:02:17.520 --> 01:02:19.780 align:middle line:84%
As you told me off
camera, this is the year

01:02:19.780 --> 01:02:21.080 align:middle line:90%
of collaboration and synergy.

01:02:21.080 --> 01:02:21.954 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: That's right.

01:02:21.954 --> 01:02:24.310 align:middle line:84%
GOLDSTEIN: So I'm synergizing
with Gregg Braden, Anita

01:02:24.310 --> 01:02:24.980 align:middle line:90%
Moorjani.

01:02:24.980 --> 01:02:26.604 align:middle line:10%
We're doing some
great things together.

01:02:26.604 --> 01:02:30.640 align:middle line:10%
With Dr. Joe Dispenza, who I
just have so much gratitude

01:02:30.640 --> 01:02:33.370 align:middle line:10%
for our collaborations
and his work

01:02:33.370 --> 01:02:35.730 align:middle line:10%
that I've been part of sharing.

01:02:35.730 --> 01:02:37.540 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: That's wonderful.

01:02:37.540 --> 01:02:40.951 align:middle line:84%
Write down the
pieces to purr by.

01:02:40.951 --> 01:02:41.950 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: That's right.

01:02:41.950 --> 01:02:42.770 align:middle line:90%
Purrfect music.

01:02:42.770 --> 01:02:45.020 align:middle line:90%
REGINA: Purrfect music.

01:02:45.020 --> 01:02:45.880 align:middle line:90%
Thank you so much.

01:02:45.880 --> 01:02:46.963 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: You're welcome.

01:02:46.963 --> 01:02:48.970 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: I really--
I mean, like I said,

01:02:48.970 --> 01:02:50.890 align:middle line:84%
I can't do a day
without music, and I'm

01:02:50.890 --> 01:02:53.454 align:middle line:84%
so happy to have your
inspiration for people

01:02:53.454 --> 01:02:55.870 align:middle line:84%
who may have kind of let music
drop from their lives a bit

01:02:55.870 --> 01:02:58.759 align:middle line:84%
to pick it back up again,
start the healing process.

01:02:58.759 --> 01:02:59.800 align:middle line:90%
Thank you so much, Barry.

01:02:59.800 --> 01:03:00.758 align:middle line:90%
GOLDSTEIN: My pleasure.

01:03:00.758 --> 01:03:01.962 align:middle line:90%
Thank you for having me.

01:03:01.962 --> 01:03:03.670 align:middle line:84%
REGINA: As I said at
the top of the show,

01:03:03.670 --> 01:03:05.470 align:middle line:84%
I couldn't live without
music in my life

01:03:05.470 --> 01:03:07.210 align:middle line:84%
and love what Barry
has shared with us.

